Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: finishing draft v8 — post-humanizer/clear-pane sweep
Draft date: 2026-07-09 23:41

INT. CABLE NEWS STUDIO - NIGHT

Election night. A wall-sized map, most of it undecided gray. Confetti
cannons stand by, unfired.

The board flips a state blue. Then another. A production assistant
claps twice, alone, then stops.

ANCHOR:
At eleven-oh-four eastern, we can now project — Zoran Marwani, the
junior senator from New York, the first DSA-affiliated nominee ever to
carry a major party — has been elected President of the United States.

The studio erupts. Balloons fall on the news desk. Someone has printed
HISTORY IS HEALING on a bedsheet in the crowd outside the window.

The COMMENTATOR, silver-haired, removes his glasses. His eyes are wet
on camera.

COMMENTATOR:
Forty-one years I've covered this building. Perhaps tonight — perhaps
tonight begins the reconciliation with a world the last administration
spent years insulting.

The chyron below him rolls: MARKETS "CAUTIOUS." ALLIES "JUBILANT."

EXT. NATIONAL MALL - DAY

Two months later. Inauguration crowd to the horizon. On the jumbotron,
PRESIDENT MARWANI, 41, hand off the Bible, already at the podium. Flags
on the stage: the fifty stars, and beside it, same height, the UN blue.

MARWANI:
(on the jumbotron)
I do not stand here to celebrate a victory. I stand here to begin a
repair. On behalf of the United States — to every nation we have
wronged — we are sorry.

The crowd roars. It rolls down the Mall in a wave.

MARWANI:
(on the jumbotron)
This is not retreat. This is not surrender. This is repair.

Under the podium feed, the chyron: NOBEL COMMITTEE AWARDS PEACE PRIZE,
CITING "THE ANNOUNCED AGENDA."

INT. C-17 CARGO BAY - DAY

Cold metal light. Pallets nose to tail, shrink-wrapped. Under the
plastic: banded bricks of hundred-dollar bills.

A LOADMASTER walks the line with a clipboard manifest. Stamped across
the top page: IRAN COMPENSATION FRAMEWORK — DISBURSEMENT 1 OF 12.

At the ramp, a young STATE DEPARTMENT AIDE in a windbreaker turns his
back to the pallets, raises his phone, and takes a selfie. He checks
it. Takes a better one.

INT. GRAND HALL, BRUSSELS - DAY

Chandeliers. A long table of ministers. The U.S. TREASURY SECRETARY
signs a document the size of a phone book; a European minister pats
his shoulder twice.

Champagne comes out on trays. The chyron on the broadcast feed:
U.S. COMMITS $200 BILLION TO EUROPEAN DEFENSE RENEWAL. Below it, a
stock ticker, all red.

ON A PHONE SCREEN

A push alert stacks over a family photo: WHITE HOUSE UNVEILS
"STEWARDSHIP ACT" — PRIVATE ASSETS ABOVE $1B TO BE ADMINISTERED IN
THE PUBLIC INTEREST.

A thumb swipes it away. Another alert lands on top of it.

INT. SENATE HEARING ROOM - DAY

Packed gallery. MAGNUS HALE alone at the witness table, reading from
a single prepared page. His voice is level and dead.

HALE:
Frontier is proud to serve the goals of this administration, at home
and beyond it.

SENATOR:
"Proud." That's good. Because some of my colleagues feel a capability
this essential shouldn't rest in private hands at all. There's a word
for the remedy. Nationalization.

The Senator leans back. Cameras click.

Hale folds his page in half, and in half again, and says nothing.

INT. ROY'S DINER - MORNING

A counter town diner. Six regulars, coffee, forks down. Nobody talks.

On the wall TV, muted: the Brussels champagne, the falling balloons,
the jumbotron apology, cycling.

EARLENE, 60s, refills BUCK's cup. Buck, 70s, feed cap, doesn't look up
from the counter. The COOK stands in the pass-through window, towel
over his shoulder, watching the muted TV. He doesn't move.

Under everything, a radio on the back shelf, volume near zero:

RADIO (V.O.):
...effective January first, the private sale and discharge of consumer
fireworks is prohibited nationwide, under the administration's binding
carbon framework. Municipal displays may apply for cultural exemption
through the...

Nobody moves to turn it up. The percolator finishes. Buck turns his
cup a quarter turn on the saucer.

BUCK:
Huh.

He drinks.

CUT TO BLACK.

> **THE FOUR OLDS** <


INT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, BROKEN BOW, NEBRASKA - DAY

Fluorescent light, carpet tiles, one teller window open. A cardboard
sign on an easel by the door: THE STEWARDSHIP ACT — WORKING FOR
COMMUNITIES LIKE YOURS. Nobody is looking at it.

CRICKET DAWES, 79, sits in the waiting area. Pressed white shirt,
buttoned to the collar. A manila folder square on his knees, both
hands on it.

INT. LOAN OFFICE - DAY

The LOAN OFFICER, 30s, tie too new, is on the desk phone as Cricket
comes in. He waves him to the chair, mouths sorry.

OFFICER:
(into phone)
— no, the culvert's the county's. That's not ours, tell him to call
Roads. Roads. R-O— I have to go.

He hangs up. Exhales. Checks a sticky note on his monitor.

OFFICER:
Mr. Dawes. Sorry. Everybody's got a flooded something this week.

Cricket sets the folder on the desk and opens it. Tab dividers,
fifty years of order. He slides the county letter across.

OFFICER:
I've got it on screen, you don't need—

Cricket slides the assessment appeal receipt across too. The
officer takes it to be polite and sets it down without reading it.

CRICKET:
County reassessed in March. Four thousand two hundred six dollars,
due the fifteenth. I have two thousand one hundred.

OFFICER:
(typing)
Okay. So there was a program for exactly this. Hardship deferral
on ag-adjacent parcels, it's — hang on.

He reads his screen. Half to himself, losing the thread of it:

OFFICER:
"Suspended pending alignment review of county remittance
instruments under the" — um. It's paused. Not paused — there's no —
there isn't a mechanism right now. Is what that means.

CRICKET:
When does it come back?

OFFICER:
It doesn't say. It's federal now. The language doesn't — it
doesn't say.

A silence. The officer scrolls Cricket's accounts, filling it.

OFFICER:
You've banked here — wow. Sixty-one years. That's longer than my
dad's been alive.

He stops scrolling. Squints.

ON HIS SCREEN: a recurring deposit line. NASA — $0.00 QUARTERLY.
Account description: DAWES, E. — ASTRONAUT (ACTIVE).

OFFICER:
There's a deposit here from NASA. Every quarter. For zero dollars
and zero cents. That's got to be a glitch, I can put a ticket in
and get it scrubbed off your—

CRICKET:
Leave it.

Too fast. Too hard. The officer looks up. Cricket sits exactly as
he was, level again.

CRICKET:
It's been there fifty years. It can stay.

OFFICER:
...Sure.

He closes that window. Sits back. Thinks. Then he pulls a form
from the drawer and talks while he fills it in, not looking up.

OFFICER:
What I can do is — our scanner's been down, there's a whole tray
of stuff that hasn't been logged, things get received when they
get received —

He stamps a date box.

OFFICER:
— so your paperwork came in next cycle. That's sixty days before
anything goes delinquent. Don't tell my branch manager.

He slides the carbon copy across.

OFFICER:
Or do, honestly. She does it too.

Cricket looks at the stamp. Puts the copy in the folder, in order,
and stands.

CRICKET:
What do I owe you?

OFFICER:
It's a bank, Mr. Dawes. You owe us four thousand dollars.

A beat. Almost a smile out of Cricket. He squares the folder under
his arm and stops at the door, half turned.

CRICKET:
Your culvert caller. If that's the one under Route 12 by the
Hollen place, that's county, he's right. But Roads won't get to it
till October. Log chain and a tractor, some Saturday. Hour of
work.

Cricket's already turning for the door. He lifts two fingers off
the folder and doesn't look back.

OFFICER:
(watching him go, something shifting)
...I'll pass that on. [beat] Every quarter, huh.

Cricket goes.

EXT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, PARKING LOT - DAY

Cricket sits in his pickup, folder on the bench seat, keys in his
hand. Through the windshield: the courthouse across the square, and
above it, the flag, moving.

He watches it one moment. Then, alone, he lets his shoulders down
half an inch and breathes out long, like he's been holding it since
before the meeting started.

CRICKET:
(to himself, dry)
"Working for communities like yours."

He almost laughs. Doesn't, quite. Starts the truck.

CUT TO:


INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

A work light on a beam. Filling half the barn: a homebuilt simulator —
plywood, angle iron, salvaged instrument panels, a real crew couch
bolted to a welded frame. Every switch is real. Every label is
hand-lettered.

Along the back wall, shelving floor to roof: spiral notebooks, hundreds
of them, spines out, each spine dated in the same hand. The first
shelf starts at 1972.

CRICKET, headset on, drops into the couch and brings the panel up.
Breakers click in a practiced order. An amber bus light steadies.

At his elbow, a ham radio rig glows. He keys it.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

STITCH (FILTERED):
There he is.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Bus B first. What's it read.

CRICKET:
Twenty-eight point one.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Huh. Okay. So it held. I still don't like the way it sagged last
week. When's the last time you pulled that relay — don't answer,
I have it here. '84. You put that relay in in '84.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Is he doing the relay again?

DUTCH (FILTERED):
It's a forty-year-old relay, is all I'm saying. I'm allowed to
say it.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
It's nineteen-oh-three, gentlemen. Commander, run your checklist.

CRICKET:
Guidance internal. Tanks at sixty-two percent, simulated. Descent
program loaded.

The barn door rolls open a foot. PEG, 77, in a house coat, sets a
thermos on the workbench.

PEG:
Tell Elmore his wife wants him off by ten.

Cricket lifts two fingers off the throttle without looking back. Peg
pulls the door to behind her.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Was that Peg?

CRICKET:
Coffee's here.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Tell her I said—

DUTCH (FILTERED):
It's an open checklist, people.

Cricket flies. Hands easy on the controls. The panel needles track.
Then an ammeter needle drops and wanders. A low buzz under the hum.

CRICKET:
Bus B again. Needle's walking.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
That buzz. Steady or does it stutter?

CRICKET:
Stutters.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Inverter case. Kick it, low left corner.

Cricket kicks the case, low left corner. The needle climbs home. The
buzz quits.

Nobody says anything about it. The checklist goes on.

CRICKET:
Three hundred feet. Drifting left. Correcting.

Silence on the net. Only the hum and the switch clicks. His hands
make small moves. The rate needle eases down. Down.

A panel lamp lights: CONTACT.

CRICKET:
Contact light. Engine stop.

A beat of quiet on the net.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Hair late on the throttle there at the end.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
The man is on the ground, Colonel.

STITCH (FILTERED):
I'm just saying what I saw.

CRICKET:
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
God willing.

Cricket keys the mic twice — two clicks. Two clicks come back. Then
two more. Then two more. He powers the rig down.

He takes a fresh spiral notebook page and writes, ballpoint, block
letters: T+2,806. BUS B CORRECTED. CONTACT 19:41. CREW PRESENT BY
RADIO.

He shelves the notebook with the others. Runs his thumb once down
the dated spines on his way to the light switch — 1974, 1988, 2003 —
and pulls the cord.

EXT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

Cricket rolls the door shut and snaps a padlock through the hasp. He
tests it with one pull.

Beyond the barn, the farmhouse porch light.

He crosses to the house, thermos under his arm.

CUT TO:


INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

Supper cleared. Peg dries dishes at the sink. Cricket at the kitchen
table with the county tax letter, a legal pad, and a pencil, doing
long division he's already done twice.

The wall phone rings. Curly cord. Cricket takes it standing.

CRICKET:
Dawes.

INT. DANNY'S KITCHEN, KEARNEY - NIGHT - INTERCUT

DANNY DAWES, 50, stands in his own kitchen, TV light moving on the
wall behind him, remote in his free hand.

DANNY:
Hey, Dad. Roads are clear down here, finally. They got the sale barn
running Thursdays again, so that's — Rachel says hi. Kids are good.

CRICKET:
Good.

DANNY:
Yeah.

A pause. Danny looks at his TV. Presses mute.

DANNY:
Dad. Maybe don't watch the news tonight.

Cricket stands there a second. Peg has stopped drying.

CRICKET:
Thank you for calling.

He hangs up. Crosses to the parlor TV and turns it on.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, PARLOR - CONTINUOUS

On the screen: the White House briefing room, then MARWANI at a
lectern, flanked by the UN flag and a folded blue banner on a stand.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
Tonight I can announce the Lunar Heritage Neutralization Accord.
Fifty-seven years ago, one nation planted its banner on ground that
belongs to all mankind. Not as conquest, we were told. And yet the
banner stayed. It stayed through every apology we owed and never
gave.

Peg comes to the parlor doorway, dish towel over her shoulder.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
Science tells us those six flags are bleached white now — fifty
years of unfiltered sun. Some call those flags of surrender. I
call them flags of peace. Let this be our gesture to the rest of
the world: we come in peace. We will retire them with dignity. We
will return them to Earth. And we will gift them — one to each
nation America has wronged. The first, to the people of Iran.

The screen cuts to a graphic. On the left: the archive photo,
Aldrin's salute, the flag hard-colored against black. On the right:
a computer rendering of the same flag, boiled white, captioned
ARTIST'S RENDERING — CURRENT CONDITION.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
In their place will fly the Harmony Banner — designed by a committee
of forty-four nations. Not one nation's pride. Not one nation's
claim. One planet's promise. The retrieval will be broadcast live,
this coming July fourth. Not Independence Day. This year, the first
Unity Day.

Applause from the briefing room press corps. Marwani does not smile.
He nods, slowly, eyes down.

Peg picks a dish back up and dries it. Dries it harder. Sets it down
in the rack with a crack of china on china. Nobody's there to hear
it.

Cricket watches to the end of the segment. An ANCHOR comes back on.

ANCHOR:
(on TV)
— being called the most generous act in the history of spaceflight.

Cricket turns the set off. Sets the remote down square on the arm
cover. Stands a moment in the dark parlor.

Then he goes back to the kitchen, takes the wall phone off the hook,
and dials from memory — seven digits, then four more.

CRICKET:
(into phone)
You watching this?

DUTCH (V.O.):
(through the phone)
Both channels. They're running that white mock-up every ten
minutes.

Neither man says anything. On the muted parlor TV behind Cricket,
visible through the doorway: the white rendering again, full screen.

CRICKET:
(into phone)
Tuesday. Early.

He hangs the phone on its cradle, gently.

CUT TO:


EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

Two black SUVs come up the drive doing about half the speed of the
county flatbed truck behind them. They park in a row, doors open
together.

Cricket steps off the porch and stands waiting, shoulders back.

ADMINISTRATOR PELL, 50s, lanyard over a zip fleece, gets out reading
a folder, and doesn't look at Cricket at all. Behind him, WADE
HALVERSEN, county deputy, mid-40s. Cricket taught him to drive a
tractor in this yard, twenty years back. Four MOVERS in matching
polos follow.

PELL:
Mr. Dawes! There he is. This is a routine action, sir, nothing
dramatic. The county's executing on the delinquent assessment —
that's their side. I'm only here for the federal paperwork.

CRICKET:
The bank logged my paperwork received next cycle. I have sixty days.

PELL:
That's the bank. The bank isn't the county. And neither one of
them is federal. You're dealing with three separate systems today,
Mr. Dawes. They don't wait on each other. Nobody's done anything
wrong here.

He hands Cricket a pink sheet without stopping his walk to the barn.

INT. DAWES BARN - CONTINUOUS

The movers roll the door wide. Daylight falls across the simulator.

MOVER #1:
What is this thing?

Nobody answers him. Pell circles the rig, checking it against an
inventory sheet.

PELL:
Item one. Homebuilt trainer, gyroscopic couch, panels — one altitude
indicator—

CRICKET:
Attitude.

Pell looks at the sheet. Makes a small correction with his pen.

PELL:
Noted.

He peels a long orange sticker off a backing sheet and lays it
across the main panel, smoothing it down with his thumb: FEDERAL
INTEREST — SENSITIVE AEROSPACE TRAINING APPARATUS — EXCLUDED FROM
PUBLIC AUCTION.

CRICKET:
Excluded from auction. So the county can't even sell it to cover
the taxes. Then this isn't about the taxes.

PELL:
Everything's compliance now. It's fairer that way. Same rules for
everybody.

The movers unbolt the crew couch. A ratchet slips; a mover barks a
knuckle and swears; Cricket hands him the correct socket off the
pegboard. The mover takes it and can't look at him.

The Deputy stands near the door with his thumbs in his belt,
studying the dirt floor.

Pell reaches the logbook wall. Hundreds of dated spines. He runs his
pen light along a shelf, pulls one notebook, flips three pages of
grid-ruled block printing.

PELL:
Personal papers.

He drops it back in its slot, crooked.

PELL:
No salvage value. Leave them.

The first dolly rolls toward the door with the crew couch strapped
to it. Then it stops.

Cricket is standing in the doorway. Square in it, feet set, hands
at his sides.

The mover looks back at Pell. Pell looks at Cricket.

PELL:
Mr. Dawes. This is executed. It's paper now.

Cricket doesn't move. Doesn't say anything either. The barn goes
quiet, six men standing around the couch on the dolly.

Pell nods at the Deputy.

The Deputy comes over slow, and stops in front of Cricket, close,
hat in his hand.

DEPUTY:
Earl.

CRICKET:
You'll have to move me, Wade.

Wade stands there a moment. Then he puts his hat on, takes
Cricket's arm with both hands, gentle, and walks him three steps
aside — and Cricket lets him, because it's Wade.

The dolly rolls past. Cricket's eyes never leave the couch, all
the way onto the flatbed.

EXT. DAWES FARM - LATER

The simulator rides the flatbed in pieces, chained at four corners.

The movers file past the porch. Peg holds the screen door open for
them and nods each one through.

PEG:
Doorframe's fresh painted. Mind it.

The Deputy is last. He hands Cricket the county copy, folded small.

DEPUTY:
There's an appeal window at the courthouse. It's open till four.

CRICKET:
Thank you, Wade.

The Deputy gets in his cruiser. Pell pauses at his SUV door and
takes in the farm, the barn, the sky. He nods at each.

PELL:
Folks, I know change feels sudden. But as the Accord reminds us —
harmony is a verb.

He gets in. The convoy pulls out, flatbed last. Dust hangs over the
drive and settles.

INT. DAWES BARN - DUSK

The barn, half empty. Where the simulator stood: a clean rectangle
of dust, bolt holes at the corners.

Cricket stands at its edge, alone a moment first. His hand comes up
and presses hard against the back of his neck. One breath. Then his
hand drops and his back goes straight again.

Peg comes in and stands next to him. Neither says anything for a
while. Straight backs, both of them.

PEG:
Supper's on in twenty.

She goes. Cricket looks at the rectangle one more moment.

Then he crosses to the workbench — they left the radio — pulls the
stool in, and keys the mic.

CRICKET:
(into mic)
Net's open. Wednesday.

Static. Then, fast:

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Copy Wednesday.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
About time.

Cricket sets the mic down and reaches up and pulls the work light on.

CUT TO:


INT. FEDERAL COMPLIANCE FIELD OFFICE - DAY

A converted storefront. Folding tables, a space heater, a laminated
poster on the wall: HARMONY IS A VERB — above it, a photo plaque,
Q3 COMPLIANCE EXCELLENCE AWARD, Pell two years younger holding it
with both hands like a fish.

Pell at a folding desk, laptop open on a call. On the screen:
DIRECTOR HOLLOWAY, gray, unreadable, better light than this room
has.

PELL:
(bright, reading off a checklist)
Dawes parcel, closed this morning. Apparatus recovered, tagged
federal interest. Full cooperation on-site. Well — cooperation.

HOLLOWAY (ON SCREEN):
That's one.

PELL:
It's a significant one, sir. Fifty years of unlogged—

HOLLOWAY (ON SCREEN):
(not really listening, flipping something off-screen)
Ohio's regional is at six this week. You're regional too. Forty-one
parcels flagged, one closure since binding. That's the number I'm
reading right now, off a spreadsheet, with your name on the tab.

Pell's smile holds a half-second too long.

PELL:
Understood. I'll accelerate the schedule.

HOLLOWAY (ON SCREEN):
Accelerate it before the Fourth. I've got a call in nine minutes.

The screen goes to the call's end card before Pell can answer. He
sits a moment, the dead laptop reflecting the fluorescent tubes
overhead.

Then he pulls the district binder over, flips past DAWES, E. —
CLOSED, and runs his finger down a long column of names. He stops
on one, uncaps a highlighter, and drags it across the line, slow,
hard enough to bleed through the page.

INSERT — THE BINDER: a column of names and addresses. One now
bright yellow: HOLLENBECK GRAIN & FEED — FLAGGED, PRIORITY REVIEW.

Pell closes the binder. Squares it on the desk. Takes his lanyard
off the hook by the door, and puts it back on.

CUT TO:


INT. ROY'S DINER - DAY

Lunch rush. Nine customers. The TV is up loud now.

ON THE TV: a Unity Day promo. A loft apartment somewhere with exposed
brick and forty people in matching UNITY DAY shirts, cheering a
countdown clock. Below them the crawl: 62 DAYS TO UNITY DAY — NATIONS
OF HONOR ANNOUNCED FRIDAY.

At the counter: BUCK, same stool. WADE the deputy, in uniform, eating
eggs two stools down, hat crown-up on the counter beside him.

The COOK works the flat-top. Zip-tied to the gas line at his elbow: a
gray box with a digital readout and a county seal. It ticks up as he
cooks.

COOK:
(to the box)
Yeah, I see you.

The diner door bell rings. Cricket comes in, takes the end stool.
Earlene has coffee in front of him before he's square on the seat.
She doesn't write a ticket. Down the counter, nobody turns his way.
Buck slides the sugar caddy to within Cricket's reach without
looking up from the TV.

ON THE TV: the watch-party promo gives way to a panel. The white
ARTIST'S RENDERING fills the screen again.

PANELIST:
(on TV)
— and honestly the flags are the last piece of it. This is a
president finishing an argument America started losing in 1969—

BUCK:
Fifty years we kept commies off the Moon. All they had to do was win
a primary.

EARLENE:
Buck.

BUCK:
I said it quiet.

Wade's cup has been empty a while. Earlene stands three feet from
the pot, wiping the counter. Wade looks at the cup, then doesn't
look at it again. He slides two dollars under the saucer, takes his
hat, and goes. The bell rings behind him.

The Cook flips the TV with the remote — to the ball game, pregame,
crowd shots from a half-empty stadium.

STADIUM ANNOUNCER:
(on TV)
...invite you to rise, as tonight's ceremonies open with "One World
Rising," performed by the Tri-Cities Children's Harmony Choir.

A synthesizer swells on the broadcast. On screen, some of the crowd
stands. A lot of it doesn't.

The Cook turns the sound down, not off, and goes back to the
flat-top.

Buck, not looking up from his coffee, starts humming. Low, to
himself. Four notes in, it's the anthem.

The Cook's spatula picks up the time against the grill edge, small,
maybe not even on purpose. At the register, Earlene hums the next
bar while she counts a stranger's change.

Nobody stands. Nobody looks at anybody. The counter hums it to the
end of the verse and stops, and the diner goes back to forks and
plates.

Cricket finishes his coffee, reaches for his wallet.

EARLENE:
It's paid.

Cricket looks down the counter. Buck watches the ball game.

CRICKET:
Obliged.

He puts his cap on and goes. The bell rings. Through the window, his
pickup pulls out, and beyond it, across the square, the courthouse
flag on its pole.

The meter on the gas line ticks up. The Cook watches it a second.
Then he goes back to the grill.

CUT TO:


INT. AMERICAN LEGION POST 219, BACK ROOM - NIGHT

A wood stove, folding chairs, a percolator going. On the wall, unit
photos going back to Korea.

GUNNY TIBBS, 71, squares the folding chairs to the table, exact.
DUTCH HAAS, 76, sits with a thick ring binder in front of him,
closed, both hands on it. STITCH McGREW, 74, is tipped back on two
legs of his chair, hat over one knee.

Cricket comes in, takes off his cap.

STITCH:
You're shorter than you sound on the radio.

CRICKET:
You're older.

GUNNY:
Gentlemen. Sit where I put you.

They sit. A beat. Four men who know each other only by radio, taking
each other in.

DUTCH:
Before anyone says anything. I've been talking to a fella at
Frontier. Cargo side, twenty years. He's sound. I'd sign for him.
Hear him out.

A knock. Gunny opens the door.

MACK BOONE, 55, work jacket, comes in with a thermos under one arm
and a folder under the other. He nods to the room, sets both down,
and lays one sheet flat in the middle of the table, squared to the
edges.

Nobody touches it. Then Dutch rotates it with two fingers, reads two
lines, and goes very still.

INSERT — THE PAGE: a federal cargo manifest. Across the header:
LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD — ARTIFACT RETRIEVAL. Line
items: SIX (6) CONTAINMENT UNITS, CLASS-A ARCHIVAL. OUTBOUND
CONFIGURATION: EMPTY.

MACK:
Six museum-grade containment units. Class-A archival spec.
Launching the last week of June, riding up empty. Somebody has to
build them, and it isn't Frontier — the fab shop's closed, you
read the papers. So it goes out to a contractor, and the
contractor's been given a budget with a note on it.

He opens the folder, takes out a printed email, and reads it flat.

MACK:
"Containment units are non-crew hardware. No certification
pathway required. Recommend sourcing retired fabrication and
aerospace personnel at heritage-labor rates."

He sets the email down next to the manifest.

MACK:
Heritage-labor rates. That's you, gentlemen. That's this whole
room.

Silence. The stove ticks. Dutch reads the header a second time.
Stitch reads it upside down from across the table. Gunny reads it
and then looks at Mack for a long moment, and Mack holds the look
and offers nothing.

STITCH:
(quiet)
Cheap old men. To box up the—

He doesn't finish it. Nobody finishes it.

GUNNY:
(to the room, not to Mack)
Somebody is going to build those boxes. Somebody's going to fold
those colors into them, on live television, with the whole world
grading the job. I'd sooner it be men who know how a flag is
handled than whoever else answers that email.

He picks up the email, reads it again, sets it down.

GUNNY:
We're the whoever-else, boys.

A short, hard laugh around the table, Stitch first. It's real.

DUTCH:
(off the spec page)
This is my standard. The '98 archival spec. Word for word.

MACK:
Nobody's improved it. Man who wrote it builds to it — that part of
the pitch writes itself.

Cricket hasn't said anything the whole meeting. Now he puts his cap
on, pushes his chair back, and walks out. The door bangs. Through
the window, his pickup's dome light comes on.

The room holds. Gunny looks at Mack. Mack doesn't move.

The door bangs again and Cricket comes back in carrying logbooks —
a two-arm load of spiral notebooks, dust still on the covers. He
drops them on the table, on top of the manifest, hard enough to
jump the coffee cups.

Fifty years of Tuesdays, dated spine after dated spine.

CRICKET:
I'm current.

Mack takes the top logbook. Flips it open. Turns a page, then
another, slower.

MACK:
Every Tuesday. Fifty years.

He closes it and sets it down, careful now, square on the stack,
with both hands.

MACK:
You'll do. Build starts Monday.

He deals contract packets around the table from the folder, one in
front of each man. Pens come out. Nobody reads past the first page
except Dutch, who reads all of it.

At the door, thermos back under his arm, Mack stops.

MACK:
One more thing, and it's in the paperwork. Client's particular
about the shop. No phones, no pictures, and nothing said outside
it — not at the diner, at church, or on your radios. Company
confidentiality.

STITCH:
Confidential flag boxes.

MACK:
That's the job.

He goes. The four of them sit with their contract packets. Gunny
gathers the coffee cups, one at a time, thinking.

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, FABRICATION BAY 2 - DAY

A vast shop floor. Gantry cranes, weld curtains, a bell
nozzle the size of a grain silo up on stands. Two hundred workers in
company blues stand in loose ranks, hoods up, gloves off.

Among them: TITO ALVAREZ, 24, welding hood pushed back, a smear of
soot to the jaw.

At a portable lectern: MIRA VESS, 40s, charcoal suit, no notes.
Off her shoulder, ADMINISTRATOR PELL with a tablet, recording. At
the back of the ranks, MACK BOONE stands with his arms folded.

VESS:
I will not waste your morning. Under the Compliance Monitorship,
Frontier's fabrication footprint exceeds the mission profile the
government has assigned us. Effective today, Bay Two is closed.
Two hundred positions are eliminated.

Silence. Then a stir through the ranks, voices rising.

WORKER:
My father cut the first nozzle ring in this bay!

VESS:
I know he did. His name is on the wall of the visitor center.

She turns a page on the lectern, unhurried, while the ranks stare.

VESS:
Terms. Severance is twelve months at full rate. Health coverage
carries the same twelve. The tooling and heavy equipment will be
declared surplus and sold for scrap at public auction. Shop
inventory will be palletized and dispositioned by an outside
logistics contractor.

Mack, at the back, unfolds his arms.

VESS:
Each of you carries a priority-rehire designation, should
operations resume. I do not expect you to believe that means
anything. Keep the card anyway.

She closes the folder on the lectern. Looks out at two hundred
faces that hate her.

VESS:
Last thing. Whatever you need to think about today — put it on me.

She steps off the lectern. No questions invited, none asked. Pell
taps his tablet and leans toward her.

PELL:
For the record, the Monitorship views this as a — a meaningful
posture of alignment. I'll be noting the, ah, expedited timeline
favorably.

VESS:
Note whatever you like.

She walks the length of the bay to the doors, heels on concrete the
only sound, two hundred men watching her go.

LATER

The ranks have broken up. Men pack toolboxes. A news crew shoots
through the fence gate: workers filing out with toolboxes and milk
crates.

Tito stands at his station a last moment. On the bench: a practice
weld, two plates joined by a bead like a row of dimes. He raps it
twice with one knuckle, picks up his hood, and walks out past Mack.

MACK:
Alvarez.

TITO:
Mr. Boone.

MACK:
You paid up at the union hall?

TITO:
Through March.

Mack picks up the practice weld off the bench, the two joined
plates, turns it over once, and sets it back down.

MACK:
Keep your tools.

TITO:
I just got fired, Mr. Boone.

MACK:
I know what happened. Keep your tools.

Mack is already walking. Tito stands there with his toolbox,
looking after him, then down at the weld on the bench.

Across the bay, Mack takes a small pocket notebook from his jacket,
writes one line, and puts it away.

CUT TO:


EXT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

A steel warehouse the size of a football field, weeds in the gravel
apron. The old county sign — CLOSED BY ORDER — has a new one bolted
over half of it: VALLEY SALVAGE & SURPLUS — CONTRACT SITE 4. AUTHORIZED
PERSONNEL.

Pickups roll in off the section road, honest daylight, work boots
stepping down.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

Mack throws breakers one at a time. Sodium lamps bang on, row by
row, until the whole dead acreage of the place stands lit: empty
auction floor, intact gantry crane, scale pit, loading docks.

The four olds stand in the middle of it, turning slowly.

DUTCH:
Three-phase power. Sixty-foot clear span. A certified scale.

MACK:
Client rents it by the month. Cheaper than a real shop.

The man-door opens. JOSS REED, 26, hoodie, work boots, a duffel.
Behind him, TITO, toolbox in hand, hood under his arm.

MACK:
Joss runs my dock at Frontier days; evenings he's mine. Fastest
hands I've got. Tito you know by his work — Bay Two, before the
cuts.

JOSS:
(seeing the old men)
Mack says be here at five and bring nothing with a battery, which
is like — literally everything is a battery — so I brought Tito.

GUNNY:
Son. Phones.

Gunny holds out a coffee can. Joss looks at it. Looks at the four
old men looking at him.

MACK:
Client confidentiality. It's in everybody's paperwork.

Joss drops his phone in. Tito's follows.

Mack unrolls the drawings on a plywood table. Official sheets,
title block stamped with a federal contract number. A crate, in
section. Dimensions, purge lines, a battery bus, a padded interior
mount drawn to close tolerance.

The kids lean in. Joss reads the header.

JOSS:
Wait. These are for the — we're building the flag boxes? So the
plan is we build fake ones and switch them, right, and the flags
never actually come down? That's the play?

MACK:
The play is we build six containment units to federal spec and
deliver them on time. It's a job, son. First one anybody's offered
Bay Two men since March.

Joss looks around the room. Nobody gives him anything.

JOSS:
Okay. Sure. A job.

Tito hasn't looked up from the drawing. He rotates it with one
finger, frowning.

TITO:
This corner joint. You spec'd a fillet here?

DUTCH:
Full-penetration bevel. Page two.

TITO:
For a box that rides up empty and comes back with a flag in it?
That's a weld for something that can't ever be allowed to fail.

DUTCH:
The spec says what it says.

TITO:
(turning the page)
Okay. Okay, yeah. But your purge line comes through two inches from
the weld. Heat's going to cook your fitting. Move it here, come in
under the frame rail, nobody ever sees it.

Dutch looks at the drawing. Looks at Tito. Takes out a pencil and
hands it to him.

Tito takes it, bends over the sheet, and starts drawing the new
line.

Dutch moves down the drawing as Tito works. He stops at the
interior mount detail. Reads the dimensions. Frowns.

DUTCH:
Interior's awful generous for cloth.

TITO:
(not looking up from his weld)
Man could about fit in there.

DUTCH:
(talking himself into his own spec)
Fifty years vacuum-baked, that fabric's a two-hundred-pound wound
now, not cloth. Fold it, it cracks along the crease like glass. Has
to ride flat, full length, stable humidity, nitrogen so the dye
doesn't oxidize on the way down, or it lands on Earth as confetti.
Only way it survives the trip.

STITCH:
(a beat, dry)
Poor flag.

Dutch looks at his own numbers a moment too long.

DUTCH:
(quiet, mostly to himself)
Hm.

He turns the page and moves on.

LATER

Tito, on his knees on the concrete, chalks a full-size crate
outline on the floor off the drawings: a long rectangle, corners
squared off a framing square.

The men stand around it, looking down at the empty chalk, each of
them quiet a beat too long.

Mack checks his watch, takes the coffee can of phones under his
arm, and kills the lights row by row on his way out.

CUT TO:


INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

The auction floor is a training floor now. A taped lane down the
concrete. A wooden step box. Four army cots. An eye chart hung on
the far wall, a long way off.

Dutch sits at a child's school desk, the binder open beside a stack
of carbon-copy forms. The top form, fresh-printed to match a
fifty-eight-year-old original: FLIGHT CREW MEDICAL EXAMINATION —
STANDARDS OF 1968.

DUTCH:
Gentlemen. NASA wrote a physical in 1968. It is the last standard
that ever mattered, and it is the one in this binder. We do all of
it or none of it.

JOSS:
(raising a hand)
Question. Is there a version of this where we just — there's
literally an app that does a full—

GUNNY:
Son.

Gunny points at Joss's wrist. The smartwatch. Then at the coffee can
on the plywood table.

JOSS:
It's a WATCH.

GUNNY:
Can, son.

JOSS:
Okay, okay — last thing it does, then. Science. For science.
Second question. Why does a crate-swapping crew need flight
physicals?

MACK:
(from the doorway, not looking up from his clipboard)
Standards are standards.

Dutch's pencil stops on the form, one beat. Then it keeps writing.

THE STEP TEST

Cricket, sleeves rolled, steps up and down on the box to Gunny's
count. Steady the whole count. Joss holds his watch near Cricket's
wrist, eyes on the little screen.

Cricket steps down. Stands easy. Breathes through his nose.

JOSS:
Two minutes post-exercise... fifty-four. Resting fifty-one. Old
dude's resting heart rate embarrassed my watch. My watch cost four
hundred dollars.

None of the old men react to this at all. Dutch writes the number
down and points at the box: next.

Joss looks at the watch, then walks it to the coffee can and drops
it in.

THE EYE CHART

Stitch, hand over one eye, all the way across the warehouse from
the chart.

STITCH:
Bottom line's got a print date on it. You want that too?

DUTCH:
(writing)
Line eleven. Nobody reads line eleven.

THE STEP TEST, AGAIN

Stitch's turn on the box. On the fourth step his knee cracks loud
enough to carry across the floor. His cadence doesn't change. He
finishes the count and steps down.

Nobody says anything about it. Dutch writes without looking up.

DUTCH:
Waiver, page nine. There were waivers in '68 too. Compensating
technique documented.

STITCH:
Anyway.

THE CRATE

The plywood mockup crate sits in the middle of the floor, lid on.
Inside it, unseen: Gunny. On the lid: a wind-up kitchen timer and
four twenty-dollar bills under a socket wrench.

Joss and Tito sit on the concrete nearby, backs to a post. Cricket
whittles a soft pine peg to fit a knothole.

TITO:
(low, to Joss)
Bet's who asks the time first.

The timer ticks. The lid does not move.

The timer rings. Dutch lifts the lid. Gunny sits up, unhurried,
looks around at all of them, and settles on the money under the
wrench.

GUNNY:
Whose twenty is on top?

JOSS:
Mine.

GUNNY:
It's mine now, son.

AT THE SCHOOL DESK - LATER

Dutch signs the fourth carbon form with a fountain pen. Squares the
stack. Files all four into the binder rings and closes the cover.

DUTCH:
Same result as 1968. All four.

He packs his fountain pen into its case. Then, as an afterthought:

DUTCH:
Slower on the step box. All four of you. I wrote it down.

STITCH:
Best year there ever was.

CUT TO:


INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

The shop, working. Crate number one stands in a welding jig,
half-skinned, purge lines run neat along the frame rail where
nobody will ever see them. TITO welds, hood down, bead steady.

Around the floor, in twos and threes, MEN FROM BAY TWO work
stations: machining, harness-lay, upholstery on a padded interior
mount. Day labor, cash rates, nobody complaining where anyone can
hear it.

AT THE PRESSURE TEST

Crate one, sealed, gauge lines running to a hand pump. Gunny checks
a clipboard, then raps the lid: two knocks — pause — two knocks.

From inside the crate, muffled: two knocks — two knocks.

GUNNY:
(to Dutch, off the gauge)
Holding steady.

DUTCH:
Cheaper than instrumenting it. A man and a wristwatch.

Inside the crate, by penlight: TITO, wedged next to the gauge,
bored, timing the hold on a wind-up watch.

INT. STITCH'S HANGAR, EAST TEXAS - NIGHT

The Tuesday net. Stitch at his workbench rig, two fingers on the
key, then off it, onto the mic.

STITCH (INTO MIC):
Y'all want to hear something about this job—

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Not on the air.

A beat.

STITCH (INTO MIC):
...Weather's been dry.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

Supper cleared. Cricket raps the table edge with one knuckle: two,
pause, two.

CRICKET:
That's how we check the box with a man inside. Two and two: all
good. Three, evenly: trouble, open it up.

PEG:
And supper?

CRICKET:
There's no knock for supper.

Peg raps the table twice, pause, twice. Then once, hard, on the
sugar bowl lid.

PEG:
All good, and there's pie.

Cricket looks at her a moment. Then he gets out his pad and writes
it down.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - LATE DAY

The big doors stand open to the gold end of the afternoon. Work
sounds. Then, one by one, the stations go quiet.

A black Suburban has pulled onto the apron. MACK walks FOUR MEN
down the crate line: thirty-somethings, fit, company windbreakers,
no names offered. They carry a tablet and a cloth measuring tape.

At the open crate, the padded interior mount finished now, one of
them steps out of his shoes, climbs in, and lies back into the
mount while another runs the tape: shoulder width, hip depth, reach.
Numbers onto the tablet. They swap. Measure again.

They don't speak to anyone on the floor. They don't smile. Ten
minutes, and the Suburban pulls out for the highway, kicking up
gravel dust.

The shop goes back to work, slower than before.

Dutch stands where he's been standing the whole time, pencil in his
hand, not writing anything.

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, TRAINING ROOM B - DAY

Drop ceiling, stack chairs, a projector. A sign-in clipboard chained
to the door. On the screen: CULTURAL ALIGNMENT — MODULE 7 OF 12
(MANDATORY).

Fifty workers in company blues, arms crossed. MACK in the third
row. JOSS near the back, dock vest, sunflower seeds.

At the front, a FACILITATOR, 30s, all teeth, clicker in hand.

FACILITATOR:
Okay! Module seven. Heritage. Big one. Now — history gives us
frameworks for thinking about the past, and some of them are bolder
than others. Slide.

The slide: a stylized portrait of MAO ZEDONG over a rising-sun
graphic, and the words: 1966 — A BOLD QUESTION: WHAT DO WE OWE THE
PAST?

FACILITATOR:
In 1966, Chairman Mao's movement asked exactly that. And their
answer was a framework called the Four Olds. Slide.

The slide, in clean sans-serif on harmony blue:

OLD IDEAS. OLD CULTURE. OLD CUSTOMS. OLD HABITS.

FACILITATOR:
Old ideas. Old culture. Old customs. Old habits. Four categories of
inherited weight. And the movement asked a community to examine
that weight together. Honestly? As an early framework for heritage
neutralization, it was ahead of its time.

In the third row, Mack uncaps a pen and copies the slide into his
pocket notebook, word for word, block letters.

The door opens. PELL steps in, tablet against his chest, and beams
at the screen.

PELL:
Don't mind me. This is the good work, folks. Centuries of ancient
Chinese wisdom in that slide.

FACILITATOR:
It's from 1966—

PELL:
Wonderful.

He stays, standing against the wall. The Facilitator clicks on.

FACILITATOR:
Now. Nobody is saying our situation is identical. But when we watch
the Accord retire tired symbols this July, we're participating in
that same brave tradition of asking: does this still serve us?

JOSS:
(not raising his hand)
What happened to the people who liked the old stuff?

Silence. The Facilitator keeps smiling.

FACILITATOR:
There were — implementation errors. In that era. Which is why
today's frameworks center dialogue. Slide.

The slide: YOUR REFLECTION HOMEWORK — IDENTIFY ONE OLD HABIT
YOU'RE READY TO RETIRE!

FACILITATOR:
Small group shares on Thursday. Sign the clipboard on your way out,
it feeds your compliance score.

Chairs scrape. Fifty men file out past the clipboard, signing
without slowing down. Pell holds the door, nodding at each man like
he knows him.

IN THE CORRIDOR

Joss falls in beside Mack in the crowd.

JOSS:
(low)
My grandpa's old habit was getting shot at over Hanoi.

MACK:
Write "coffee." Everybody writes coffee.

Joss looks at him. Mack peels off toward the dock without another
word, notebook square in his jacket pocket.

CUT TO:


EXT. FRONTIER LAUNCH COMPLEX - DAY (NEWS FOOTAGE)

Steady news-helicopter footage: the booster on its transporter, long
as a grain elevator on its side. On its flank, fifty feet of painted
stars and stripes.

A cherry-picker rises alongside. Two painters in white roll primer
over the field of stars, top to bottom, one pass at a time. The
footage does not cut away. The anchor has stopped talking.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, PRESS ROOM - DAY

Vess at a podium. Cameras. A REPORTER mid-question.

REPORTER:
— but whose decision was it to paint over the—

VESS:
Mine. I ordered the repainting. The Accord specifies neutral
mission livery. Paint is cheaper than a receiver. That math is my
job.

REPORTER:
And Mr. Hale's position on—

VESS:
The board meets Thursday. Bring it.

She steps down.

INT. ROY'S DINER - DAY

The repaint footage on the wall TV, the white roller crossing the
last star.

The Cook reaches up and turns the set off. Black screen. He goes
back to the grill. Nine customers eat in the quiet. The carbon
meter ticks.

The door bell rings. Cricket comes in, takes the end stool.

Nobody says anything. But Buck doesn't slide the sugar down, and
Earlene's coffee takes a while getting there, and when it comes she
writes the ticket.

Cricket drinks his coffee alone, pays the ticket, and puts his cap
on. The bell rings behind him.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - DUSK

Floor-to-ceiling glass. MAGNUS HALE stands at it, hands in his
pockets, looking down the flight line at the real thing: the
booster, primer-white flank drying under the work lights. A crew
tarps it for the night.

The door. Vess comes in, stops beside him at the glass. They stand
there, not looking at each other, the white rectangle below them.

She sets a folder on his desk on her way out. The door closes.

Hale doesn't turn around.

CUT TO:


EXT. PIONEER FIELD, MINOR-LEAGUE BALLPARK - NIGHT

Small park, big lights, maybe nine thousand people. Kids on the
outfield berm. The four olds and Peg sit together down the
third-base line, ball caps and popcorn. A full row of empty
seats flanks them, in a sold-out park.

PA ANNOUNCER (V.O.):
Ladies and gentlemen, please rise, as tonight's ceremonies open
with "One World Rising," performed by the Tri-Cities Children's
Harmony Choir.

The crowd gets up slow, hands in pockets. A backing track swells
through the PA: synthesizer, chimes. The children's choir starts,
small and dutiful, on the infield grass.

Down the first-base line, BUCK, feed cap in his fist, flannel
tucked in for the occasion, stands looking at the flag pole beyond
center field, the flag up there lit against the dark.

Buck opens his mouth and starts to sing the national anthem, alone,
off-key, too loud, four full bars by himself against nine thousand
people's silence and a children's choir.

Nobody joins him. Then the row behind him joins him.

Then the section. Then the far bleachers, ragged, out of time with
each other, gaining. The backing track keeps playing underneath,
chimes and all, buried under the voices. The children's choir looks
at their director. The director looks at nine thousand people, drops
her hands, and turns around to face the flag pole.

The four olds do not sing. Hats off, on their feet. Gunny stands at
attention, thumb along his trouser seam. Stitch's jaw is tight.
Dutch holds his cap over the exact center of his chest. Cricket
watches the crowd, row on row of them finding the words.

Peg sings.

By the last line it is nine thousand voices and no melody to speak
of and the light towers humming over all of it.

The note dies off across the parking lots. A beat of quiet.

By the concourse rail, a COMPLIANCE KID, 20s, polo and lanyard,
stands with his tablet half-raised. He looks from the tablet to the
stands and back. He lowers the tablet and puts it away.

The crowd sits. The game just starts, like nothing happened, first
pitch a called strike.

On the scoreboard: TONIGHT'S POST-GAME LIGHT SHOW BROUGHT TO YOU BY
THE UNITY FUND. A BOY, 8, two rows down from the olds, tugs his
father's sleeve.

BOY:
Is the light show the one with the booms?

FATHER:
Not anymore, bud.

Cricket looks down the row. Dutch, Stitch, Gunny look back at him.
Nobody says anything. They sit, and put their caps back on, one by
one.

CUT TO:


INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Late. One work lamp. DUTCH alone at the plywood table with the
build drawings, his binder, and a slide rule.

He counts scrubber cartridges on the parts shelf against a line in
the drawing. Counts again. Sits down slow.

He works the slide rule. Checks the drawing's spare-cartridge rack,
four slots, not one, against the swap interval called out in his
own notes. Writes a figure. Works it again from the other
direction, and writes the same figure, and boxes it, twice.

INSERT — THE PAD: CARTRIDGE RACK, 4 SPARES/UNIT. SWAP EVERY ~15
HRS. = 4 SWAPS, FULL TRANSIT.

Dutch looks at the boxed line a long time. Then he gets up, crosses
to crate number one, finished, gleaming under the tarp, pulls the
tarp off, undogs the lid, and opens it.

Inside is a molded couch with a head cradle and restraint webbing,
shaped exactly like a man.

Dutch stands there looking into it a long time, one hand on the
lid.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - THE NEXT EVENING

All of them: the four olds, Joss, Tito, and MACK, called in. The
build drawing lies on the plywood table with Dutch's pad on top of
it, the boxed figure facing up.

DUTCH:
I told this room the fabric needs to ride flat. Stable. Purged, so
the dye doesn't go on the way down. I believed my own math on that.
(beat, tapping the rack detail)
But this — four spare cartridges, swapped every fifteen hours or
so — that's not a purge charge. You seal a purge charge once and
leave it alone. Something that needs swapping on a schedule is
using it up. There's only one thing on this crate that uses up air.

He lets that sit.

DUTCH:
There is no version of this drawing where nobody's inside it.

He turns the drawing around to face Mack.

DUTCH:
It's a life-support system with a museum sticker on it. I should
know. I wrote it. And I talked myself out of my own spec sheet.

He lets that sit one beat.

DUTCH:
And those four young fellas with the measuring tape stopped coming
around. So. Who's riding, Boone?

Silence. Joss looks from Dutch to Mack. Tito has stopped moving.

Mack doesn't answer right away. He looks at the drawing a long
moment, really looks at it, like he's seeing it for the first
time, doing arithmetic nobody taught him.

Then he looks around the table, one face at a time, and says it
plain.

MACK:
So. You gentlemen want to go to the Moon?

Joss sits down on a sawhorse without checking it's there.

JOSS:
Wait. WAIT.

MACK:
The mission flies July first no matter what this building does.
Six crates go up empty and six flags come down. Or four crates go
up full. That's the whole choice. There isn't a third thing.

GUNNY:
And if this room says no?

MACK:
Then six crates fly empty, and I lose track of some scrap, and
we all went to a lot of trouble over a carousel.

Quiet. The stove has no fire in it tonight, and nobody moves to
light one.

Stitch gets up, walks to the open crate, and looks into the couch
a moment. Then he climbs in, lies back, and sets his hat on his
chest.

STITCH:
Snug.

Gunny crosses to the gear shelf and starts counting scrubber
cartridges into ranks of four, marking the shelf edge with a
grease pencil.

GUNNY:
Well. Now what do they take from us — cancel my Medicare on the
Moon?

Dutch squares his pad on the drawing.

DUTCH:
The spec holds. I sized it.

Every face turns to Cricket, last.

Cricket looks at the crate a long moment. Then he walks over to
it, sits down on the edge of it, and starts unlacing his boots.

CRICKET:
Somebody time me getting in. We'll want a number.

Tito comes over and raps the crate wall twice with one knuckle.

TITO:
(quiet)
She'll hold.

MACK:
(quiet, and for the first time all night, not selling anything)
You understand there's no backing out once you're up there. Bad
heart at four g's, your age, no doctor closer than a quarter
million miles.

GUNNY:
(not unkindly)
Boone, I've buried better men than me for worse reasons than this.
Sit down or go home. Either's fine. Quit standing there doing
arithmetic on our behalf.

A beat. Mack sits. Takes out his pen.

JOSS:
You're all insane. What do you need from me?

MACK:
The build order changes Monday. Nothing else does.

He takes out the pocket notebook, writes one line, and puts it
away.

CUT TO:


INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

The shop after hours. The crew (four olds, two kids, Mack) around
the plywood table. The finished crate with the couch in it stands
lid-open where everyone can see it, because nobody's pretending
anymore.

MACK:
From tonight, everything changes how it moves. Nothing electronic.
No phones, no email, no cloud. Nothing with a battery you didn't
build yourself.

JOSS:
Then how do two hundred guys and four states coordinate a—

DUTCH:
Handwritten letters. The ham net, on schedule, in code. A book
cipher. Cricket has the year and the month.

Cricket sets a swollen 1971 Reader's Digest on the table.

JOSS:
That's insane. That's — that's Revolutionary War stuff.

GUNNY:
They've got every algorithm ever written. We've got Valley Forge.

Joss opens his mouth. Closes it.

EXT. RURAL MAILBOX, NEBRASKA - DAY

A weathered hand puts a letter in a mailbox and raises the little
red flag. The envelope, handwritten: TRI-COUNTY FEED COOPERATIVE,
RE: PARTS.

EXT. MAILBOX ROW, SOUTH CAROLINA LOWCOUNTRY - DAY

Another envelope, another red flag up. The mail carrier takes it
without a glance, tosses it in the tray between coupon packs.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

Peg reads from a handwritten strip of paper, glasses down her nose.

PEG:
Fourteen. Two. Nine.

Cricket thumbs the Reader's Digest to page fourteen, column two,
counts nine words down, and writes one word on a pad.

PEG:
Six. One. Eleven.

He flips, counts, writes. Peg looks at the pad over his shoulder.

PEG:
That's a grocery list.

CRICKET:
This week it is.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Tito, respirator up, lays a stencil across crate one's flank and
rolls paint through it: LOT A — OLD IDEAS. Taped to the crate beside
him, his guide: a page torn from a pocket notebook, four lines in
Mack's block handwriting.

He peels the stencil, checks the edges, taps the crate twice.

LATER

Tito shoots two frames of the finished couch with a film camera,
winds the film down, and drops the canister into a Folgers can
half-full of them. The can goes into the bottom of his toolbox.

EXT. GUNNY'S PORCH, SOUTH CAROLINA - NIGHT

A morse key wired to a TV tray. Sweet tea. Gunny sends, slow and
exact, frogs loud in the dark past the porch rail.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

Cricket copies letter groups off the air onto the pad, line after
line. He keys two clicks. Two click back.

EXT. DAWES BARN - LATER

The barn window lit. Inside, faint, morse ticking.

Peg crosses the yard in her house coat, stops at the barn wall,
raps it twice — pause — twice. Goes back to the house.

Inside the barn, without breaking his copy rhythm, Cricket reaches
up and flicks the work light off-on once.

CUT TO:


EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

A commercial flatbed grinds up the drive, VALLEY SALVAGE &
SURPLUS painted on the door. On the bed, chained at four corners:
the simulator, in its pieces.

Every piece wears a fresh orange stencil: SCRAP — LOT 44-C.

Cricket comes off the porch. The DRIVER, 50s, coveralls, swings
down with a clipboard.

DRIVER:
You Dawes?

CRICKET:
I'm Dawes.

DRIVER:
Sign for lot 44-C. Scrap conveyance, buyer's copy. Somebody paid
the freight to here, don't ask me who, I drive.

Cricket takes the clipboard. Flips the top page. Reads.

The line items: HOMEBUILT TRAINER COMPONENTS. DISPOSITION: SOLD AS
SCRAP — NON-FUNCTIONAL. RELEASED FROM FEDERAL SURPLUS HOLDING BY
DISPOSAL CONTRACTOR.

Cricket looks at the flatbed. The panels sit intact under the
chains, gauges unbroken, his hand-lettered labels facing the sky.

CRICKET:
Says non-functional.

DRIVER:
It does say that.

The driver looks at the load, then at Cricket, then at his watch.

DRIVER:
I got a two o'clock in Ogallala.

Cricket signs. The driver unbinds the chains.

Peg watches from the porch as the two men walk the pieces into the
barn on a hand truck, one load at a time.

PEG:
Barn's where it was.

DRIVER:
Yes, ma'am.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

The simulator stands whole again on its welded frame, bolted down
through the same four holes. The orange SCRAP stencil still on the
couch rail. Cricket, socket wrench in hand, looks at the stencil a
moment, and leaves it.

He drops into the couch. Breakers click in the practiced order. The
amber bus light steadies.

He pulls the headset on and keys the rig.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Tuesday.

STITCH (FILTERED):
There he is.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Bus B. What's it read.

CRICKET:
Twenty-eight point four. Better than it left.

A beat on the net.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Run your card, Commander.

Cricket sets his hand on the throttle. Above the panel, taped where
a mission patch would go: the pink county seizure sheet, folded to
show the words SENSITIVE AEROSPACE TRAINING APPARATUS.

CRICKET:
Guidance internal.

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, CARGO INTEGRATION HALL - DAY

Clean-room bright. Six crates on cradles in a row — museum-grade,
brushed alloy skins, purge fittings, gauges. Stenciled big on their
flanks like stock lots:

LOT A — OLD IDEAS. LOT B — OLD CULTURE. LOT C — OLD CUSTOMS. LOT D —
OLD HABITS. LOT E — SUPPLEMENTARY CONTAINMENT. LOT F — SUPPLEMENTARY
CONTAINMENT.

Dock crew in bunny suits. MACK with a clipboard. JOSS on the crane
controls. And walking the line with a tablet: PELL.

PELL:
Random re-weigh. Compliance is a rhythm, folks. Random means random.

MACK:
They weighed in at fabrication.

PELL:
And now they'll weigh in at integration.

The crane takes LOT A. Sets it on the floor scale. The SCALE TECH,
40s, coffee thermos on the console, reads the number against the
manifest.

SCALE TECH:
Lot A. Three-eighty declared... four-eleven-two.

Pell stops walking.

PELL:
Again.

SCALE TECH:
Four-eleven-two.

PELL:
Weigh B.

LOT B: 413.0. LOT C: 412.6. LOT D: 409.8. Four crates, all heavy,
thirty-some kilos each. Pell comes to the console and reads the
display himself — manifest line, crate serial, number, in the right
order, fast.

PELL:
Thirty kilos over, times four crates. That's a hundred and twenty
kilos of something, Mr. Boone.

MACK:
Could be the couch upgrade. Archival spec revision come through in
March—

PELL:
Re-run it. Cell check first.

The hall has gone quiet enough to hear the air handlers.

The Scale Tech runs the load-cell check. Taps cell three with two
knuckles. The number stutters: 411.9... 408.2... 413.5.

He frowns at it. Looks up at the crate on the platen, the
stencil marked OLD IDEAS, the purge gauge holding steady. Looks at
his own clipboard.

A long moment. Joss, up in the crane cab, sits absolutely still.

The Scale Tech writes on the log sheet, reading aloud as he writes.

SCALE TECH:
Calibration drift, cell three. All four reads invalidated.
Corrected tare applied. Within tolerance after correction.

He initials it, tears the copy, hands it up to Pell, picks up his
thermos, and walks back to his console. He does not look at Mack on
the way.

Pell reads the sheet. Reads it again. Files it in his packet,
squared to the corner.

PELL:
Hm.

He walks the row one more time and stops at LOT F.

PELL:
Where's the environmental cert on this one?

MACK:
Rides with the master manifest.

PELL:
The master manifest references an attachment E-6. There is no
attachment E-6 in my packet.

Mack flips his clipboard. A beat too long.

MACK:
That's a paperwork question. Paperwork's Monday.

PELL:
It's Thursday. Lot F is impounded until I hold E-6 in my hand.
Forty-eight hours, Mr. Boone, or it comes off the manifest. It
doesn't fly.

He peels an orange IMPOUND sticker and smooths it across Lot F's
seam with his thumb, both passes, careful.

Then, at LOT D, he stops, takes out a pen, signs the inspection tag
himself, and slots it in the holder: INSPECTED — J. PELL.

PELL:
The Accord appreciates everyone's patience today.

He goes. The crew breathes out. Joss climbs down from the crane,
gray in the face. Mack watches Pell's door swing shut.

MACK:
(quiet, to Joss)
Get word up the net. Gunny's gear just went in the penalty box.

CUT TO:


INT. SENATE HEARING ROOM - DAY

The same room from the election-year grilling. The same SENATOR,
higher on the dais now. In the witness chair: MIRA VESS, alone, no
counsel, water glass untouched.

SENATOR:
Ms. Vess. You run Frontier day to day.

VESS:
I do.

SENATOR:
And Mr. Hale — the founder, your... partner — what does he run?

A small laugh through the gallery at the pause. Vess does not join
it.

VESS:
Magnus holds the title of founder and chief engineer. Day-to-day
authority rests with me. It has for six years.

SENATOR:
Has Mr. Hale ever expressed contempt for this administration's
space policy? For the Accord?

VESS:
Frequently. In colorful terms. I can provide dates.

The gallery stirs. On the press bench, pens move.

SENATOR:
You'd testify your own founder is hostile to the mission your
company is flying.

VESS:
I'd testify he talks. Senator, Magnus Hale has not directed a
covert anything in the six years I have run his company. He is not
built for quiet. He posts what he thinks. Usually before breakfast.
You have his feed. Subpoena his drafts folder if you want the rest.

Laughter, open now. The Senator lets it run.

SENATOR:
Some of my colleagues feel that attitude alone justifies a federal
receiver on the company through Unity Day.

VESS:
A receiver wouldn't know this company in six months. Your
broadcast is in nine weeks. The Accord flies on schedule if the
company stays in the hands that run it. Mine.

SENATOR:
And Mr. Hale?

VESS:
Watch him as closely as you like. He's loud. His calendar's
clean.

The Senator sits back and caps his pen.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - CONTINUOUS

Dark but for the wall screen: Vess in the chair, the chyron — VESS:
FOUNDER "NOT BUILT FOR QUIET" — and a phone in Hale's hand.

On the phone, a draft post, cursor blinking: My COO and the mother
of my children just

His thumb hovers. Holds.

He backspaces it to nothing, sets the phone face down on the desk,
and watches the rest in the dark.

ON THE WALL SCREEN

PANELIST (V.O.):
— because when even Mira Vess won't defend him, what's left to
defend? The board should thank her. Frankly the country should.

CUT TO:


EXT. DAWES FARM, MAILBOX - DAY

Cricket walks the drive, takes the mail. Bills, a seed catalog —
and one heavy envelope, government linen, eagle on the corner.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - DAY

The letter flat on the table between them. Peg reads over her
glasses.

PEG:
(reading)
"...administrative review has restored annuity status retroactive
to separation... enclosed disbursement reflects adjusted back
period..."

She slides the check out of the envelope. Looks at the number. Sets
it down facing Cricket.

The check: $184,306.00.

PEG:
And the county sent one too. Lien's released. Taxes marked
satisfied, the whole assessment.

CRICKET:
Fifty years, they never paid a nickel. Zero dollars, zero cents,
every quarter on the dot. Now, nine weeks before their launch,
somebody in Washington finds my file and gets generous.

Peg looks at the check. At him.

PEG:
It would fix the roof, the truck, the next ten years.

CRICKET:
It would.

He picks up the check, evens its edges against the table, opens the
hutch drawer, and lays it inside, flat, under the county's pink
seizure copy he never threw away.

He shuts the drawer.

CRICKET:
If they're paying the roster, the roster's real. File says
astronaut, active. I'll bill them when I'm back.

Peg looks at him a long moment. Then she takes the empty envelope,
folds it once, and drops it in the stove kindling.

PEG:
Supper's on in twenty.

CUT TO:


INT. FEDERAL FIELD OFFICE - NIGHT

Pell at his desk, late. His phone buzzes: a forwarded photo, grainy,
time-stamped 1:14 AM — box trucks backed up to the Tri-County
Auction Barn, loading doors lit.

Pell looks at it a long time. Then he prints it, pins it to a cork
board, and picks up the phone.

EXT. GUNNY'S PORCH, SOUTH CAROLINA - NIGHT

Frogs. A police scanner murmurs on the TV tray, county traffic,
numbers and street names.

Gunny sets down his sweet tea, leans to the morse key, and sends:
two clicks. A pause. Two clicks.

EXT. COUNTY ROAD, NEBRASKA - NIGHT

Hay trucks — three of them, loaded high and tarped — pull out of
the auction barn's back gate, running lights only, and spread out
onto three different section roads.

EXT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAWN

Four black SUVs and a box van of INSPECTORS in wind-breakers roll
up the gravel. Pell, tablet in hand, motions: roll the doors.

The doors roll.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - CONTINUOUS

A carousel.

Dismantled across the whole floor — carved horses in ranks on
padded trestles, brass poles in racks, a ring of men with brushes
and gold leaf and coffee. Two hundred of them, easy. The
gantry crane holds a palomino mid-air on soft slings.

A banner across the back wall: CUSTER COUNTY FAIR CENTENNIAL —
CAROUSEL RESTORATION PROJECT. VOLUNTEERS WELCOME.

An AM radio plays farm futures. Nobody stops working.

Pell walks in slow. An inspector behind him lifts a tarp: horse
legs, numbered with masking tape. Another checks the scale pit:
swept concrete, a shop-vac parked in it.

A PAINTER, 60s, gold leaf on his knuckles, looks up from a horse's
bridle.

PAINTER:
You want a brush, friend? We're behind.

Pell doesn't answer. He walks the ranks of horses, taps one on the
rump, reads the job board: a hauling schedule, handwritten, pinned
next to feed-store receipts and a fair-committee letterhead.

He checks the photo on his tablet against the loading doors. Same
doors. He looks at the crane, the swept pit, the two hundred men
painting.

PELL:
(reading the banner, flat)
"Volunteers welcome."

He stands in the middle of it a moment, tablet hanging from his
hand.

PELL:
Two hundred volunteers. On a Tuesday.

PAINTER:
County pays for the gold leaf.

Pell looks at him. The Painter holds his eye, friendly, brush
loaded and waiting.

Pell turns and walks out. The inspectors trail him. The doors roll
shut behind them, and everyone holds still one beat — brushes up,
nobody moving —

Then the AM radio changes to a ballgame, and the brushes come back
down.

EXT. COUNTY ROAD - MORNING

The federal convoy heads back down the two-lane. It passes, coming
the other way, a hay truck loaded high and tarped, then a second,
then, a mile on, a third.

At the wheel of the third, cap low, arm out the window: TITO. A
whip antenna bolted to the fender ticks in the wind.

The convoy doesn't slow. The hay rolls on.

CUT TO:


INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

Cricket packs a canvas kit bag on the workbench, item by item off a
handwritten list: logbook, slide rule, a zippo, a folded photograph
he doesn't look at.

Headlights swing across the wall. A truck door. Then DANNY in the
barn doorway, keys still in his hand.

He looks at the simulator. At the orange SCRAP stencil. At the kit
bag.

DANNY:
I know what's in the barn, Dad. I've known a year. I figured you'd
tell me when it mattered.

Cricket zips the bag halfway and stops.

DANNY:
I'm not going to say any of the things. About your age, or the law,
or Mom. You'd just stand there and let me finish.

CRICKET:
I would.

Danny looks at the logbook shelf — the fifty years of it — and back
at his father. Whatever he came to say next, he doesn't say it.

DANNY:
You need a driver?

CRICKET:
Thursday. Four a.m. Dress like a farmer.

DANNY:
I am a farmer.

He goes. Cricket zips the bag the rest of the way.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, BEDROOM - NIGHT

The kit bag open on the bed. Peg repacks it. Rolls each item tight,
wedges them square.

PEG:
You'll want the—

CRICKET:
It's in there.

PEG:
And the spare glasses.

CRICKET:
Front pocket.

She holds up two pairs of socks.

PEG:
Take the good ones. Not the gray, they've quit.

She swaps them. Presses the lid of the bag flat with both hands,
testing the pack of it.

LATER

The house dark. In the sewing room, one lamp. Peg at the Singer,
the kit bag's canvas lid under the needle. She sews something small
inside the underside of the flap — three sides, a pocket's worth of
stitches — snips the thread, and smooths the canvas down flat so
that nothing shows at all.

INT. ALVAREZ KITCHEN, EAST LOS ANGELES - NIGHT

A small kitchen, saints on the wall, an old Singer on its own table
by the window.

LITA, 80s, and Tito stand on opposite sides of the kitchen table.
Between them, spread the table's whole length, a hand-sewn flag,
fifty-one stars in the field, one more than it should carry.

They fold it together. Lengthwise. Lengthwise again. Then Lita
starts the triangle folds from her end, tight and sharp, turning
the colors over and over into themselves while Tito keeps the
tension, and neither of them says one word.

The last fold tucks. A triangle of stars, packed tight.

Lita holds it a moment. Then she takes a small SAINT CHRISTOPHER
medal on a pin from her apron pocket and pins it deep inside the
last fold, where it will touch nothing but flag.

She puts the triangle in Tito's hands.

He kisses her forehead. Takes his cap off the chair, and goes.
Through the window, under the streetlight, he sets the triangle on
the truck seat with both hands.

Lita sits back down at the Singer and turns off the lamp.

CUT TO:


EXT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, MAIN GATE - PRE-DAWN

4:00 AM by the guard shack clock. A farm truck rolls up to the
contractor lane. DANNY at the wheel, seed cap. In the bed and cab:
four men in gray coveralls — CRICKET, DUTCH, STITCH, GUNNY — with
lunch coolers and a laminated work order.

The GATE GUARD scans the order: VALLEY SALVAGE & SURPLUS — ARCHIVAL
UNIT FINAL SERVICING, BAY 1. Four names that aren't theirs.

GATE GUARD:
Y'all know where you're going?

GUNNY:
Son, we were servicing this bay before your daddy made the varsity.

The guard waves them through. Danny eases the truck in, knuckles
white on the wheel, eyes forward.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, CARGO INTEGRATION HALL - PRE-DAWN

The six crates in their cradles. Pell, early, stands at LOT F
peeling his own impound sticker while MACK holds out a document.

PELL:
Attachment E-6. Notarized. Backdated to March, I notice.

MACK:
Filed in March. Copied slow.

PELL:
Everything about you people is slow.

He initials the release, unhappy about it, and walks the row one
last time — a long look down the stenciled flanks — then off toward
the observation mezzanine.

THE SERVICING

The four "contractors" work the crates with purge carts and torque
wrenches, unhurried and unnoticed. Joss's dock crew moves around
them, seeing nothing.

One by one, unhurried, each old man steps up on a cart, into a
crate, and lies back into the molded couch.

Cricket is last. He sets his kit bag between his knees, looks up at
Joss standing over him with the lid hoist — and past him, at the
hall's high steel, the cranes, the morning light coming up the
windows.

CRICKET:
Tuesday net's at nineteen hundred, your frequency card's taped
under the console. Don't improvise.

JOSS:
Copy. No improvising.

CRICKET:
And Joss. Thank your dad for the radio.

Joss looks at him a second.

JOSS:
Fly good, old man.

The lid comes down. Torque gun, eight bolts, a hiss as the purge
line seats.

Joss raps the lid: knock-knock — pause — knock-knock.

From inside, muffled and exact: knock-knock — knock-knock.

He moves down the line. Raps LOT B. Answer. LOT C. Answer. LOT D.
Answer. Four crates, four heartbeats.

At LOT E, Tito — contractor coveralls, cap backwards — sets a
canvas-wrapped triangle into a padded corner mount, checks it
twice with two knuckles, and seals the lid on the rest of the gear:
tarped shapes, latched cases, gear.

THE RANDOM CHECK

A DOCKWORKER, 50s, Frontier badge, twenty-year lanyard tape on the
clip, works the pre-stack checklist crate to crate. Torque seals.
Purge pressure. Latch flags.

At LOT D, the checklist stops him: one latch flag showing amber.
Procedure. He unslings his wrench, breaks the inspection latch, and
lifts the service panel.

Inside, packed in the molded couch, kit bag between his knees, eyes
open: CRICKET DAWES, looking straight up at him.

One second. Two. Three.

The Dockworker looks at the manifest on his clipboard. At the
inspection tag in the holder: INSPECTED — J. PELL. At the old man
in the crate, who does not blink.

The Dockworker resets the latch. Seats the panel. Signs the line.

INSERT: the checklist, block letters: LOT D — ALL CLEAR.

He moves to LOT E without looking back.

THE STACK

The transporter takes the crates out the high door into the dawn,
six in a row, stencils catching the light: OLD IDEAS. OLD CULTURE.
OLD CUSTOMS. OLD HABITS. SUPPLEMENTARY CONTAINMENT. SUPPLEMENTARY
CONTAINMENT.

Mack and Joss watch from the dock edge. Mack signs the contractor
crew OUT. Four names, one pen. No one is watching.

JOSS:
Net's quiet. Two clicks if it stays that way.

MACK:
Go home. Sleep.

Joss almost smiles. Doesn't manage it. The crates ride away toward
the stacking cell, small against the building, then smaller.

CUT TO:


EXT. FRONTIER LAUNCH COMPLEX, PAD 1 - NIGHT

The rocket stands in its own light, primer-white flank blank where
the flag was. Vapor bleeds off the stages and rolls down the hull.

INT. CARGO BAY, CRATE D - NIGHT

Blackness. Then a small amber bus light steadies, and there is
Cricket's face by its glow, flat on his back in the molded couch,
kit bag between his knees.

Through the structure: pumps starting somewhere far below, a hum
climbing through the frame into his shoulder blades.

He puts one hand flat on the lid above his face.

INT. KENNEDY BALLROOM, WASHINGTON - NIGHT

Chandeliers and a thousand guests. UNITY EVE in living flowers
across the stage. At center, a scale model of the Harmony Banner
under glass.

Marwani works the room in black tie, handshake to handshake. On a
screen the size of a barn door: the live pad feed.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - NIGHT

Rows of consoles. In a glassed VIP row, VESS, standing, arms
folded. Beside her, PELL with a commemorative program.

At a podium off the floor, HALE reads to a camera, voice level and
dead.

HALE:
Frontier is honored to carry the Lunar Heritage Neutralization
Accord to flight. Tonight belongs to the community of nations.

He steps away from the podium before the light on the camera is
off.

EXT. PAD 1, CREW ACCESS ARM - NIGHT

The HARMONY CREW crosses in white suits, helmets under arms:
CMDR. BRANDT, silver at the temples; MAJ. LINDQVIST; OBSERVER SHEN,
a head shorter, mission patch of the 44-nation banner.

At the hatch, Brandt pauses. Looks up the whole height of the
stack, a long way, to where the vapor curls off into the dark. Then
he goes in.

INT. ROY'S DINER - NIGHT

Full house, quiet. Every face turned to the TV: the pad, the clock.
Earlene has stopped pretending to wipe anything.

BUCK:
There she goes in a minute. Ours. Whatever's riding her.

Nobody answers him. The Cook comes out of the kitchen and stands
with his towel over his shoulder.

INT. KENNEDY BALLROOM - NIGHT

Marwani takes the stage, flute in hand. The room hushes. On the
barn-door screen behind him, the countdown clock walks down through
ninety seconds.

MARWANI:
Tonight a rocket rises with no flag on its side. Think of that.
Not conquest. Not pride. Repair. A machine built by the old
America, flying the first errand of the new one.

INT. CARGO BAY, CRATE D - NIGHT

The hum has become a shudder. Dust ticks off the lid seam in the
amber light. Cricket's breathing stays even, eyes open.

MARWANI (V.O.):
(over the ballroom PA, distant)
— so raise a glass, to a healed sky —

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - NIGHT

LAUNCH DIRECTOR (O.S.):
— three. Two. One.

EXT. PAD 1 - NIGHT

Ignition. The night goes orange for a mile. The rocket climbs off
the pad on a column of fire, slow, then faster.

INT. KENNEDY BALLROOM - NIGHT

The screen floods the ballroom with launch light. A thousand flutes
tip together. Applause swells over the engine roar in the feed.

INT. CARGO BAY, CRATE D - LAUNCH

Weight. The couch takes Cricket deep into its molding, jaw pulled
back, hand still flat on the lid. The amber light dims under the
load — holds — comes back.

INT. ROY'S DINER - NIGHT

The rocket climbs on the TV. The diner watches it go, faces lit by
the screen. Wade the deputy, at the counter in civvies, has his hat
off, held against his chest.

EXT. SPACE - LATER

Engine cutoff. The roar stops all at once. The ship coasts, sunrise
crawling up the curve of the Earth below, the white hull going gold
along one edge.

INT. CARGO BAY - CONTINUOUS

Dark and still. Cricket's kit bag floats up off his knees to the
end of its lanyard and hangs there, drifting.

A sound in the dark bay. Two knocks. Pause. Two knocks.

From another crate: two knocks — two knocks.

A third crate answers. Then a fourth.

The bay hangs quiet, four amber lights burning in four sealed
boxes, the Earth turning gold in the one small window across the
bay.

CUT TO:


INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - SHIP'S NIGHT

The bay dark except for panel standby glow. Six crates ranked and
strapped, four amber lights showing at their vent slits. Beyond the
one small window, the Earth, whole, the size of a dinner plate and
shrinking.

A knock sequence taps out of crate B — long-short rhythms, patient.

INT. CRATE C - CONTINUOUS

Dutch, amber-lit, a pocket notebook against his knee. He pencils
letters as the knocks land, one at a time:

INSERT — THE NOTEBOOK: "STITCH ASKS IF ANYONE ELSE'S HOTEL HAS ROOM
SERVICE."

Dutch reaches up without looking and knocks his reply on the crate
wall, slow and even.

INSERT — THE NOTEBOOK, next line: "TOLD HIM. TAKE IT UP WITH THE
SPEC AUTHOR."

INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - LATER

The service rotation. Crate A's panel swings open from inside, slow,
and GUNNY floats out in thermal underwear and socks, a small kit
bag tethered to his wrist.

He works crate to crate in the dark, unhurried: swaps a scrubber
cartridge through Crate B's service port. Checks Crate C's purge
gauge with a penlight hooded in his fist.

At Crate D, he unclips a steel thermos from his kit, opens the vent
hatch, and passes it through.

CRICKET (O.S.):
(a whisper, from inside)
Obliged.

Gunny closes the hatch to a half-inch. Turns for his own crate —

The bay door seal hisses. Light spills in.

Gunny goes flat behind Crate F, one hand on a strap, socks floating.

MAJ. LINDQVIST drifts in with a flashlight, coverall sleeves rolled,
running a routine sweep. The beam walks down the stencils: OLD
IDEAS. OLD CULTURE. OLD CUSTOMS. The beam crosses the half-open
vent hatch on Crate D.

Lindqvist frowns at it, pushes the hatch flush with one finger
until it clicks, checks nothing else, and drifts back out. The door
seals.

Dark again. Gunny lets go of the strap.

He crosses to the small window instead of his crate. Holds the
frame with both hands.

Out there: the Moon, filling a third of the glass, gray and coming.

Gunny looks at it a long time. Then he pushes off, floats back into
Crate A, and pulls the panel shut behind him. The amber lights burn
in the dark.

CUT TO:


INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - SHIP'S DAY

Work lights on. OBSERVER SHEN floats the crate line alone, tablet
tethered to his wrist, stylus in hand. Cargo audit: serial by
serial, seal by seal.

He reads Crate A's stencil — OLD IDEAS — and enters the serial. The
purge gauge: nominal. He moves down the line.

OLD CULTURE. Serial. Gauge. Entry.

OLD CUSTOMS. Serial. Gauge. Entry.

At OLD HABITS — Crate D — he stops.

He holds still, head tilted a few degrees.

INT. CRATE D - CONTINUOUS

Cricket, flat in the amber glow. A shadow lies across his vent
slit and does not move.

He stops breathing. All at once, mid-breath, held.

INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - CONTINUOUS

Shen drifts closer to the crate. Reads the inspection tag:
INSPECTED — J. PELL. Reads the serial. Checks the gauge — nominal,
steady.

Then he takes off one glove, wedges it under his arm, and lays his
bare palm flat on the crate's skin.

He leaves it there.

INT. CRATE D - CONTINUOUS

Cricket, breath held, eyes on the lid an inch above his face. The
only sound in here is his own heart, loud, and getting louder.

INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - CONTINUOUS

Shen's palm on the metal. His face gives nothing. Five seconds.
Eight.

Behind him, the bay door: CMDR. BRANDT drifts halfway in.

BRANDT:
Shen. Burn prep. Straps in twenty.

Shen doesn't startle. He lifts his palm from the crate, works his
glove back on, and makes an entry on the tablet.

INSERT — THE TABLET: LOT D — SEALS INTACT. PURGE NOMINAL. NO
ANOMALY.

He follows Brandt out. The lights bank down to standby. The door
seals.

INT. CRATE D - CONTINUOUS

Cricket lets the breath go, slow, through his teeth.

A moment. Then, from Crate C, very soft through the walls: two
knocks.

Cricket reaches up and answers: two knocks.

The amber light burns. Nothing else moves.

CUT TO:


EXT. DAWES FARM, PORCH - DAY

One black SUV waits in the drive, washed this time. A
young WHITE HOUSE AIDE in a good coat stands at the bottom of the
porch steps, holding a phone out flat on his upturned palm.

On the porch: PEG, arms crossed. DANNY beside her, sleeves rolled.

MARWANI (V.O.):
(from the phone, warm)
Mrs. Dawes. I hope I find you well. Is the Commander home?

PEG:
He's out.

MARWANI (V.O.):
Of course. Mrs. Dawes, the country is about to share a difficult,
beautiful day, and the President — I — would rather share it whole
than divided. There are men, I'm told, for whom the past fifty
years were a wound. Your husband trained for something that was
taken from him. I cannot give him back the years. But I can give
him the rest.

Peg says nothing. The aide's arm is getting tired.

MARWANI (V.O.):
The pension, made whole — that's done, as a gesture. The record,
amended: Apollo Eighteen entered into the rolls with his name on
the crew. Flown status, conferred by executive order — the title,
the wings, the history. All of it, Mrs. Dawes. On one condition.
Unity Day passes undisturbed — and your husband watches it at
home. On his porch. Visibly. Where the country can see a great
American at peace with a new world.

Wind in the shelterbelt. Peg looks at the phone on the young man's
palm.

PEG:
I'll pass it along if he phones.

MARWANI (V.O.):
Mrs. Dawes—

PEG:
You have a good day now.

She goes inside. The screen door claps. Danny stays a beat longer,
looking at the aide, then follows her in. The aide is left holding
his own phone out to a farmhouse.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD, NEBRASKA - NIGHT

Joss's truck on a high section road, tailgate down, a wire antenna
run from a mast clamp to a fencepost. Joss works a morse key by
red flashlight, a paper of cipher groups taped to the tailgate.
Danny leans on the fender, watching the sky.

JOSS:
Pass is six minutes. It's enough.

He keys. Stops. Listens to the hiss.

INT. CRATE D - NIGHT (LOW EARTH ORBIT)

The amber light. Morse, thin and far, ticking in Cricket's earpiece.
He copies letters onto his pad, steady, no expression.

The pad fills: PENSION WHOLE. RECORD AMENDED. FLOWN STATUS. EXEC
ORDER. CONDITION: HOME ON PORCH UNITY DAY. VISIBLE.

Cricket looks at the word VISIBLE a moment.

He knocks on the crate wall: two — two. From crate C, two — two
back. From B. From A.

Then he takes the key wired at his hip and sends, short and even.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD - CONTINUOUS

Joss copies onto the tailgate paper, letter by letter, lips moving.
Then he stops keying back. Reads it. Reads it again.

DANNY:
What's he say?

JOSS:
(reading)
"Tell him: you can't give back what you never had."

Danny looks at the paper. At the sky.

JOSS:
There's more.

Joss's pencil finishes the last group.

JOSS:
"Dawes out."

Overhead, among all the fixed stars, one moving point of light
crosses the dark, west to east, steady.

They watch it go all the way to the horizon.

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - NIGHT

The floor quiet and full. On the main screen, the ship's track
curls away from the Earth line toward a drawn gray circle.

FLIGHT DIRECTOR:
Flight controllers, go no-go for trans-lunar injection. Guidance.

CONTROLLER (O.S.):
Go.

FLIGHT DIRECTOR:
Propulsion.

CONTROLLER #2 (O.S.):
Go.

FLIGHT DIRECTOR:
Harmony One, you are go for TLI.

In the glass VIP row, Vess stands alone at the rail. Behind her,
Pell works through a commemorative program with a highlighter.

BRANDT (V.O.):
(on the loop)
Copy. Go for TLI.

INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - CONTINUOUS

The bay in standby glow. Four amber lights at four vent slits.

A clunk through the structure. Then the push — long and gathering —
straps creaking taut against the crates.

INT. CRATE D - CONTINUOUS

Cricket pressed back into the couch, the amber light steady, his
hand flat on the lid. The burn goes on. And on.

Then: cutoff. Weightless again. The kit bag floats up to the end
of its lanyard.

INT. CRATE C - CONTINUOUS

Dutch, pencil out, runs figures in the notebook margin — velocity,
a time, an arc — and boxes the result, twice.

INSERT — THE NOTEBOOK: BURN NOMINAL. COAST 62 HRS. NO ABORT MODES
REMAIN.

He looks at the boxed line a moment. Then he knocks on his crate
wall: two — two.

Two — two, from D. Two — two, from B. Two — two, from A.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - CONTINUOUS

The track on the main screen bends out of Earth's neighborhood for
good. Applause on the floor, brief and professional.

Vess watches the line go. She lets go of the rail, one finger at a
time.

FLIGHT DIRECTOR:
Trajectory nominal. Sixty-two hours to lunar orbit insertion,
gentlemen. Get some sleep.

Pell caps his highlighter.

PELL:
Well. Nothing stopping it now.

Vess doesn't answer him.

CUT TO:

> **END OF ACT TWO** <


INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - DAY

Every console manned, every screen the same: the gray surface
coming up under the lander's camera, dust beginning to streak.

BRANDT (V.O.):
(on the loop)
Two hundred feet. Down at three. Picking up some dust.

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

Standing room only. The TV huge in the corner. Nobody eats.

INT. JOSS'S TRUCK, RIDGE ROAD - CONTINUOUS

Joss and Danny shoulder to shoulder in the cab, a phone propped on
the dash streaming the feed, the ham rig silent beside it.

BRANDT (V.O.):
(on the phone, compressed)
Fifty feet. Forty. Contact light — engine stop.

The dust settles on every screen in America. HARMONY ONE stands on
the Sea of Tranquility, primer-white, flagless.

The diner watches, still. Somebody's coffee goes cold untouched.

INT. CARGO BAY - CONTINUOUS

No one on Earth sees this. Touchdown slammed the crate rack.
Straps took the load wrong, something in Crate C slid half a foot
and stopped hard.

Cricket keys the mic, his own breath still catching.

CRICKET:
(low)
Sound off.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Here.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Here.

A beat. Nothing from Crate C.

CRICKET:
Stitch.

Nothing.

CRICKET:
(sharper now)
Elmore.

A wet, ugly cough comes over the channel.

STITCH (FILTERED):
(raspy)
...M'fine. Bit clean through my tongue is all.

A breath goes around the net.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Don't you go quiet on this net again, Colonel.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

EXT. SEA OF TRANQUILITY - LUNAR DAY

Silence and glare. The lander's shadow long across the regolith.

The crew works the base-station deployment: BRANDT and LINDQVIST
wrestling a solar array true, SHEN anchoring a comms mast, all
three helmet-cams feeding Earth. A camera boom pans slow across
the site for the broadcast.

Behind the lander, in its blind spot, the cargo ramp is down.

Four crates stand open on the ramp, lids back, couches empty.

Four suited figures move in the lander's shadow. Suits fifty years
old, patched and re-hosed, the NASA meatball bright on every chest.
On one wrist cuff, a small brass museum tag turns on its wire.

They cross-load gear from crates E and F onto the BACKUP ROVER:
tarped bundles, latched cases, a long soft-sided sleeve strapped
diagonal. Practiced and unhurried, not one move wasted.

The last man aboard is the tallest. He settles into the rover's
rear rack seat, raps the fender twice — pause — twice.

The rover pulls away from the lander in a slow arc, out of the
shadow and into the sun, four men and their freight aboard. Tire
tracks unspool behind it across ground no one has touched in fifty
years.

It gets small against the gray. Then it drops behind a rise and is
gone.

Behind it, the tires throw a rooster-tail of dust that doesn't
billow the way dust should. No air to hold it. It arcs, clean and
ballistic, and comes down all at once, in one place, unnaturally
neat.

At the base station, Brandt straightens from the solar array,
turns to check the horizon out of pure habit, and stops.

He stares north. A thin haze, catching the sun, exactly where
nothing should be moving.

ON THE ROVER — the four of them go still. Engine cut. Parked
exactly where the rise should hide them, and doesn't quite.
Cricket's hand stays flat on the throttle. Nobody breathes into a
mic.

Brandt watches the horizon. Three seconds. Four.

LINDQVIST (O.S.):
(over comms)
Commander, panel four's ready for your sign-off.

A beat longer. Then Brandt turns back to the array, already
reaching for his checklist.

BRANDT:
(on the loop)
Base station nominal. Harmony One, beginning retrieval operations
at first light tomorrow, per the program.

Behind him, far off over the rise, the last of the dust settles.

CUT TO:


EXT. SURVEYOR CRATER, APOLLO 12 SITE - LUNAR DAY

The prime rover crests a low ridge, camera boom high, three suits
aboard. Below: the Apollo 12 descent stage, gold foil still bright,
experiment packages ranked where men left them in 1969.

LINDQVIST:
(reading from a cue card clipped to his cuff)
"We arrive as guests of history, to relieve it of its oldest
burden—"

He stops reading.

The flag is missing. A socket hole stands in the gray. Around it,
the bootprints are recent, and they aren't theirs. Wheel tracks
lead in and out of the site.

BRANDT:
Harmony, Site One. The artifact is... not present.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - CONTINUOUS

Rows of faces, nobody moving. On the main screen, the empty socket
hole, full screen.

FLIGHT DIRECTOR:
Say again, Harmony One?

BRANDT (V.O.):
The flag is gone. The site is otherwise intact. We observe recent
surface activity. Bootprints. Vehicle tracks.

INT. UNITY DAY PAVILION, WASHINGTON - CONTINUOUS

A daytime stage dressed in harmony blue, schoolchildren holding
little Harmony Banners. Marwani mid-remarks at a podium, teleprompter
rolling. Behind him, the giant screen cuts from the live feed to a
graphic reading PLEASE STAND BY: UNITY DAY.

An AIDE climbs the stage steps and whispers. Marwani keeps smiling
at the children while he listens.

INT. JOSS'S TRUCK - CONTINUOUS

The phone on the dash shows a jittery re-stream of the raw feed,
chat scrolling too fast to read.

JOSS:
They can't cut the raw loop. It relays through nine countries.

DANNY:
Where are the flags, Joss?

Joss looks at the ham rig. Says nothing. Two clicks come out of it,
soft. Then two more.

EXT. FRA MAURO, APOLLO 14 SITE - LATER

The rover parked. Three suits standing at another socket hole,
another ring of prints, the same wheel tracks arriving and leaving.

Lindqvist holds his cue card, doesn't read it.

ON A STREAMER'S FEED (INSET)

A man in a gaming chair, veins out.

STREAMER:
There were NEVER any flags! Fifty years of soundstage! They're on
the Moon looking for PROPS, people! WAKE UP!

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

On the TV, the socket hole again. Buck turns his cup a quarter
turn.

BUCK:
Somebody took 'em.

EARLENE:
Took 'em where, Buck? It's the Moon.

Buck drinks his coffee. A smile starts on his face, slow.

EXT. FRA MAURO - CONTINUOUS

Brandt stands over the wheel tracks. Follows them with his visor to
where they run off northwest, dead straight, out of sight.

He switches to the private crew loop. Click.

SHEN:
(on the private loop)
Commander. The possibility must be raised. If the artifacts were
never — if the landings themselves were—

BRANDT:
Don't.

Silence on the loop. Shen looks at the bootprints. Fifty years of
undisturbed prints ring the socket, the new ones laid over them,
crisp-edged and fresh.

BRANDT:
Mount up. Last site on the program.

LINDQVIST:
Tranquility Base.

Brandt takes one more look northwest along the wheel tracks, dead
straight, toward Tranquility.

BRANDT:
Whoever they are, they're not hiding their driving.

CUT TO:


EXT. APPROACH TO TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

The prime rover parked at the foot of a long, low rise. The three
Harmony astronauts climb it on foot, single file, the camera boom
and their helmet-cams feeding Earth.

BRANDT:
(on the loop)
Harmony, on foot, one hundred meters from Tranquility Base
perimeter. Site should be visual past this rise.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - CONTINUOUS

Every screen shows the bobbing helmet-cam view: gray ground, black
sky, the rise coming up.

The chest-mounted camera clears the rise before any man's helmet
does.

On the main screen, over the lip of ground: COLOR.

A CONTROLLER stands up so fast his headset cord snaps taut. Nobody
says anything. The image steadies as Brandt keeps climbing, seeing
nothing yet but his own boots.

FULL FRAME, TO EARTH:

Six American flags, vibrant red, white, and blue against the
black. Five stand in a wide ring around the low hill of Tranquility
Base. At the center, on the original pole, the first flag stands
again, raised where it fell in 1969.

Inside the ring, four webbed aluminum lawn chairs. A squat steel
grill on legs, hoses run to a bottle, a curl of vapor flashing off
its seams. A card table. On the card table, a cooler.

And four old men in fifty-year-old suits, three seated, one
standing at the grill with a long spatula, all facing the rise.

Behind the party, four emptied crates stand on end in a row, side
by side, stenciled faces out:

OLD IDEAS. OLD CULTURE. OLD CUSTOMS. OLD HABITS.

Beside the grill, on a workshop flagpole smaller than the six,
stands a hand-sewn flag with one star too many.

A tripod stands off to the side. It's their own camera, a red
light on it, the feed already live on Earth's internet.

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

The TV. The ring of flags. The lawn chairs.

Buck is on his feet. So is everybody.

BUCK:
There they are.

INT. UNITY DAY PAVILION - CONTINUOUS

Marwani, mid-sentence, feels the crowd's eyes go past him. He
turns. The screen behind him holds the ring of flags, forty feet
tall.

The schoolchildren, front row, see flags and lawn chairs and a
cookout.

They cheer.

INT. FRONTIER TRAINING ROOM (WATCH PARTY) - CONTINUOUS

Folding chairs, sheet cake. The FACILITATOR from Module 7 stands
frozen with a paper plate, reading her own slide off the crate
lids.

ON A NEWS PANEL (INSET)

A PANELIST freezes mid-sentence, ear to his earpiece.

PANELIST:
(on TV)
— I'm being told those suits — the suits are the Apollo artifacts
Frontier donated to the heritage program last spring. They're
wearing the museum pieces.

ON A STREAMER'S FEED (INSET)

The streamer, mid-rant, stops. His jaw works. Dead air, chat
avalanching.

EXT. TRAM STOP, WARSAW - NIGHT

Strangers packed around one phone. The ring of flags glows off
their faces. Somebody starts to clap. Others join. It spreads down
the platform.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Brandt's eyes finally clear the rise. He stops walking. Lindqvist
stops behind him. Shen stops last.

The three of them stand on the lip of the ground, looking down at
the most illegal Fourth of July in human history.

At the grill, the tall suited figure sees them, straightens up,
and raises the spatula, unhurried, all the way up.

Hold on that.

CUT TO:


EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

Brandt comes down the rise slow, hands visible, Lindqvist and Shen
behind him. The ring of flags stands around them, colors hard in
the sun. The tripod camera's red light burns.

Brandt stops ten meters out. Keys his radio.

BRANDT:
Switching to channel two. Let's talk privately, gentlemen.

The old man at the grill doesn't move. The one in the second
chair, CRICKET, gray stubble behind the visor glass, keys the OPEN
loop.

CRICKET:
We'll talk right here. Whole world's listening anyway.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - CONTINUOUS

The Flight Director looks at the loop status: OPEN. Every word
going to Earth raw. Nobody moves to change it.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Brandt looks back at his crew, then walks closer. He reads the
crate lids left to right, the small flag with too many stars, the
grill.

LINDQVIST:
(blurting)
Where did you even COME from?

CRICKET:
We came in the mail.

A beat.

BRANDT:
(formal, for the record)
This site is designated for retrieval under the Lunar Heritage
Neutralization Accord. I am required to ask who you are and by
what authority you interfere.

The old men look at each other. Cricket stands up out of his lawn
chair, unhurried, and faces him.

CRICKET:
We're the backup crew. NASA never processed us out. We're still on
the roster, son. This is our mission.

STITCH:
(from his chair, not getting up)
This here's our camp. Pack the fuck off.

INT. WHITE HOUSE, COUNSEL'S OFFICE - CONTINUOUS

Four LAWYERS around a speakerphone, laptops open. One of them has
a personnel file on screen: DAWES, E. — ASTRONAUT (ACTIVE). A
fifty-year column of quarterly entries: $0.00. $0.00. $0.00.

LAWYER #1:
Tell me this is a database error.

LAWYER #2:
It's been signed off every quarter since 1972, by career staff,
under four statutes. And three months ago somebody reactivated the
annuity — we did — which means this administration AFFIRMED the
status—

LAWYER #1:
So they're not trespassers.

LAWYER #2:
They're federal personnel on their duty station. If that crew
removes them on camera, the crew of a foreign-flagged mission will
be laying hands on serving American officers, live, on the Fourth
of July.

Silence around the speakerphone.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Shen steps forward, past Brandt, toward the nearest flag in the
ring.

All four old men come out of their chairs at once. Nobody
signals. They stand between him and the colors.

Shen stops.

The one from the grill, GUNNY, tallest, spatula still in hand,
looks down at him through the visor glass a long moment. Then
points the spatula, once, back at the Harmony rover.

The open loop stays silent. No one moves.

BRANDT:
(on the loop, eyes on the old men)
Harmony copies. Control, Harmony requests instructions.

The old men sit back down, one at a time, Cricket last. Gunny goes
back to the grill and flips what's on it.

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - CONTINUOUS

The Flight Director stands at his console, headset half-off,
looking at a message on his screen: WASHINGTON DIRECTS: PROCEED
WITH RETRIEVAL PER ACCORD SCHEDULE. ACKNOWLEDGE.

He looks at it a long moment. Then he takes the headset all the
way off and sets it on the console.

A new voice comes onto the loop anyway, accented and smooth,
patched in from off-site.

ACCORD COORDINATOR (V.O.):
Harmony One, this is Accord Coordination, Geneva. You are directed
to proceed with retrieval of all six artifacts. Immediately,
please.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Brandt stands in the ring of flags. He looks at the old men in
their lawn chairs. At the first flag, center, on its 1969 pole.

BRANDT:
(quietly, on the loop)
Copy, Geneva.

He walks to the nearest flag in the ring. Plants his boots. And
reaches for the staff.

Four old men come out of four lawn chairs and step between him and
the colors in one motion. A line, shoulder to shoulder, visors
level, Cricket at the center.

Brandt's glove stops a foot short. He is looking at a color guard.

Gunny, at the end of the line, keys the open loop. His voice comes
slow and even, to Brandt, and to every living room on Earth.

GUNNY:
You want 'em? Come through us.

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

Everybody is already standing. Buck's fist comes down on the
counter, once —

BUCK:
U-S-A!

— and the diner takes it up, coffee cups rattling.

DINER:
USA! USA! USA!

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - CONTINUOUS

The carousel crew around a paint-spattered radio, brushes down,
two hundred voices pounding it out, gold leaf shaking off a
horse's bridle.

EXT. HIGHWAY OVERPASS - CONTINUOUS

Pickup trucks parked fender to fender. Men drop a flag the size of
a bedsheet over the rail into the wind above six lanes. Horns
below, hundreds, leaning on it.

EXT. CUSTER COUNTY FAIRGROUNDS - CONTINUOUS

The Fourth of July fair, in full swing. At its center, gold leaf
bright under the lights: the carousel, restored, turning, packed
with kids. Every grown-up around it is on their feet, chanting
at a phone screen somebody holds up.

INT. BROOKLYN LOFT, WATCH PARTY - CONTINUOUS

The UNITY DAY shirts crowd, forty of them, on their feet. Half of
them chant USA, USA, caught up in it, before some remember
themselves and stop, hands over mouths.

Some don't stop.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD - CONTINUOUS

Joss, truck door open, working the morse key fast. Danny beside
him, hands on top of his head.

INT./EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

In Cricket's earpiece, thin and far, morse: three letters, over
and over.

Behind the glass, Cricket swallows once.

Brandt lowers his arm. Steps back one step.

SHEN:
(private loop)
Commander. Your orders—

BRANDT:
(private loop)
I know my orders.

He keys back to open.

BRANDT:
Geneva, Harmony One. The site is... occupied by personnel asserting
jurisdiction. Requesting political guidance.

Long static. On the card table, unhurried, Gunny deals four hands
of cards.

CUT TO:


INT. ROY'S DINER - DAY

The TV: PRESIDENT MARWANI at the briefing-room podium, flags of
forty-four nations pinned behind him.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
This morning I directed Frontier Aerospace to restore mission
control and end this provocation. Not because we fear four old
men. Because the world deserves the day it was promised. The
company's obligations are clear. So are the consequences of
failing them.

He steps away from the podium without questions.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, PRESS ROOM - DAY

Live lights. Cameras banked three deep. HALE at the podium, a
single prepared page in his hand. Off-stage, in the dark of the
wings: VESS, arms folded, watching.

Hale flattens the page on the podium. Reads, in the dead voice.

HALE:
"Frontier Aerospace condemns the unauthorized occupation of the
Tranquility site, and will comply fully with federal direction
to..."

He stops. Looks at the next line. The room waits, shutters
clicking.

He folds the page in half. And in half again. And sets it down,
squared to the podium's edge.

HALE:
I can't read this one.

He looks straight into the bank of cameras. When he speaks again,
the flatness is gone.

HALE:
Somebody used my rocket to do the finest thing an American has
done in fifty years. You want somebody to punish for that? You
want to nationalize me? Go. Fuck. Yourself.

Flashes. Bedlam. Aides somewhere off-camera shouting the feed
down, and failing, because the feed is his.

Hale steps off the podium. A REPORTER stands into his path,
recorder out.

REPORTER:
Mr. Hale — the President is saying you've betrayed the
community of—

HALE:
(walking, not turning)
Tell the commie he can eat shit.

He passes Vess in the wings. Stops. The two of them look at each
other, one beat, two.

He keeps walking. She watches him go. The corner of her mouth
moves.

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

Frozen. Then BUCK laughs, one short bark, and slaps the counter.

The COOK looks at the carbon meter on his gas line. Then he turns
the flat-top burners up, all the way, all of them.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, LOBBY - DUSK

Doors bang open. PELL crosses the marble at speed with two FEDERAL
MARSHALS, tablet under his arm, lanyard swinging.

PELL:
(to the desk, not stopping)
Where is the override room, and where is Mira Vess?

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, VESS'S OFFICE - NIGHT

Corner office, lights low, the launch complex out the glass. VESS
stands behind her desk. On the desk: one folder, squared to the
blotter.

The door opens. PELL, marshals behind him.

VESS:
They wait in the hall.

PELL:
They're federal marshals.

Vess says nothing. She waits.

Pell looks at her. Then nods the marshals back. The door clicks.

PELL:
Ms. Vess. I am here for the mission override, and I am past
asking nicely.

VESS:
There is no override. The ship answers its crew. You built the
compliance regime, Administrator. Nothing at this company moves
without a signature. You know that better than anyone.

She opens the folder. Takes out the first page. Lays it in front
of him, turned to face him.

VESS:
The integration re-weigh. Four anomalous mass readings,
invalidated by calibration drift, accepted into the federal record.
Countersigned.

His own signature, at the bottom.

VESS:
Flight performance reserve, revised upward eleven percent six weeks
before launch. Also countersigned. Nobody asked why. Nobody ever
asks why a margin gets padded. It's the one number everyone's
grateful somebody was careful about.

VESS:
Attachment E-6, releasing containment unit F from impound.
Initialed.

The second page goes down. His initials.

VESS:
Inspection certification, containment unit D. Personally executed.

The carbon of the orange tag: INSPECTED — J. PELL. She lays a
fourth page beside it: the re-weigh acceptance, unit D line
highlighted.

VESS:
Twice.

Pell looks down at the pages. At his own name, four times, in his
own hand.

PELL:
You scheduled my inspections.

She takes out the last page and lays it down: a printed calendar
memo. RANDOM COMPLIANCE RE-WEIGH — WINDOW PROPOSED PER M. VESS
OFFICE.

PELL:
(quiet)
Random means random.

VESS:
It does.

Pell stares at the pages. His hand moves toward them, stops.

PELL:
The scale tech. Yours?

Vess looks at him and says nothing at all.

PELL:
You understand what you've — if I take this public, you go to
prison.

VESS:
With every document bearing your signature, Administrator.

She comes around the desk, past him, to the door, and stops with
her hand on it.

VESS:
You wanted the company to cooperate. The company cooperated. The
country didn't.

She opens the door and walks out through the marshals, unhurried,
down the hall, gone.

Pell stands alone in her office, in front of the desk, the pages
lined up facing the empty chair.

After a moment, he sits down in front of them, in the visitor's
chair, and doesn't touch anything.

CUT TO:


INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - NIGHT

Dark. The launch complex lit below the glass. Hale at the desk,
tie gone, the phone in his hand.

He types two words. Looks at them.

INSERT — THE PHONE: Look up.

He posts it, and sets the phone face down on the desk.

INT. ROY'S DINER - NIGHT

The phone behind the register buzzes. Earlene reads it. Shows the
Cook.

EXT. DAWES FARMHOUSE - NIGHT

The yard dark. The porch light comes on.

Off. On. Off — on, on.

PEG on the porch in her house coat, hand on the switch, working it:
two — pause — two. Two — pause — two.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD - NIGHT

Joss's truck headlights answer across the dark section land: two —
two. Danny, standing in the bed, watches farmhouse after farmhouse
come alight down the valley — porch lights snapping on, some
steady, some flashing, spreading fence line to fence line.

EXT. PIONEER FIELD, BALLPARK - NIGHT

Empty stands. The GROUNDSKEEPER at the breaker panel throws the
light towers on — off — on, whole banks at a time, the field
strobing under them.

EXT. AMERICA - NIGHT (AERIAL)

Suburb grids pulse. A skyline flickers block by block. Highways
run bright with flashers. The dark country between cities fills
with pinpoints, porch by porch, until the whole country is lit.

INT. REGIONAL GRID CONTROL ROOM - NIGHT

A wall of monitors, load curves spiking hard off the top of the
chart. A GRID OPERATOR stares at it, headset on.

GRID OPERATOR:
(into headset, disbelieving)
That's more draw than the whole state used to pull on the Fourth.
Every firework stand lit at once. Where's this even coming from?

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

Buck watches his own porch light blink through the window. Doesn't
look away from it.

BUCK:
(to nobody, satisfied)
Good.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

The card game. Stitch, holding his hand of cards, has looked up,
past the flags, at the Earth hanging in the black.

STITCH:
Y'all.

They look up. The four olds. Then Brandt. Then Lindqvist. Then
Shen.

The night side of the Earth is flickering. Waves of light crawl
across it — coastlines pulsing, whole seaboards going bright and
dark and bright.

Seven visors tilt back, the Earth small and bright in every one of
them.

Nobody says anything for a long time. The cards hang in Stitch's
glove, forgotten.

At the grill, without looking away from the Earth, Gunny reaches
over and turns down the burner.

CUT TO:


EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

The Earth still ripples with light. Gunny opens the sealed press
on the grill. Rows of burgers, vapor flashing off them.

Brandt watches from three meters. His next words go out on the
open loop, unguarded.

BRANDT:
...is that a burger?

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - CONTINUOUS

A beat of dead air on the floor. Then a controller snorts. Then
the whole back row goes.

ON SCREENS AROUND THE WORLD

The clip replays instantly, captioned in forty languages. IS THAT
A BURGER? crawls under the ring of flags on every network.

EXT. TRAM STOP, WARSAW - NIGHT

The platform crowd, bigger now, howls.

INT. GENEVA, ACCORD PRESS ROOM - DAY

The ACCORD COORDINATOR at a lectern, gray suit, grim.

ACCORD COORDINATOR:
The retrieval program remains, in the Accord's view, scheduled —

The press row laughs, not politely. He looks down at his notes,
and a minister seated behind him checks his phone and grins before
he can stop himself.

INT. WHITE HOUSE, PRESS BRIEFING ROOM - DAY

The PRESS SECRETARY at the podium, gripping it.

PRESS SECRETARY:
The President believes the situation at the site has — evolved —

A laugh from the back row. Then the middle rows. She stands in it,
looking down at her briefing book.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Brandt looks at the burgers a long moment. Then he keys the open
loop, formal, every word chosen.

BRANDT:
Geneva, Harmony One. Site survey complete. There is nothing at
Tranquility to retrieve. There is a color guard, on station, under
national colors. Harmony One stands down.

Static from Geneva. Nothing else.

Gunny loads a burger onto the long spatula and extends it across
the three meters, steady.

Brandt looks at his crew. Lindqvist's glove comes up: go on.

Brandt takes the burger and holds it up beside his visor, the
ring of flags and the flickering Earth behind him.

The tripod camera's red light burns. On every screen on Earth, the
same frame.

Lindqvist accepts one too, laughing inside his helmet, silent
behind glass.

Shen stands apart, arms folded. Gunny plates a burger anyway and
sets it on the card table, in front of the empty fourth chair,
facing him.

It sits there. Shen looks at it, and away.

INT. ROY'S DINER - NIGHT

The frame on the TV: Brandt and the burger. The Cook's flat-top is
full edge to edge. He starts plating burgers nobody ordered,
passing them down the counter, waving off every wallet that comes
out.

Buck raises his coffee cup to the TV and holds it up a moment.

CUT TO:


EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LATER

The card table cleared. Off to the side, angled toward the black
sky: a short rack of three mortar tubes, welded neat, cabled to a
firing box on the card table.

The four olds stand in a loose line inside the ring of flags.
Brandt and Lindqvist stand behind them. Shen stands apart, arms
folded. But he's there.

Gunny takes a folded photocopy from his wrist pocket and opens it
with both gloves. When he speaks, it is slower, and older.

GUNNY:
John Adams. Wrote this to his wife, July of 1776, about this day.

He reads.

GUNNY:
"It ought to be solemnized with pomp and parade. With shows,
games, sports, guns, bells, bonfires and illuminations — from one
end of this continent to the other. From this time forward.
Forevermore."

He folds the paper and puts it away.

GUNNY:
Two hundred and fifty years, and here we all are. One end of the
continent to the other — and a little past it.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - CONTINUOUS

The carousel floor. Two hundred men, Joss, Danny, and TITO around
the radio and a live feed. On the loop, Cricket's voice.

CRICKET (V.O.):
Tito Alvarez. You built the tubes. Count us down.

Tito looks around the barn. Two hundred faces looking back. Danny
puts a hand on his shoulder.

Tito leans to the microphone.

TITO:
(into the mic)
Tres... dos... uno.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Gunny's glove closes the circuit.

The first shell rides a hard straight spark into the black — no
arc, no drift, dead true — and breaks.

RED. A perfect sphere, edges clean, expanding and expanding and
not stopping, no air to slow it, and no sound at all.

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

The whole room lit red off the TV. Nobody blinks.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

The second shell breaks WHITE — a sphere inside the fading red
one, rings within rings, drifting up through itself in the vacuum.

EXT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, PORCH - NIGHT

Peg on the porch, the TV's glow through the window laying white
light across her face. Her hand is on the porch light switch. She
leaves it on, steady now.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

The white sphere hangs over the six flags and the small
fifty-one-star one. Cricket steps forward, next to the first flag,
the one raised back up where it fell.

He keys the open loop: to the crew, the diner, Warsaw, the barn,
Geneva, every person on the lit face of the Earth.

CRICKET:
It's Independence Day.

A beat. The whole channel, the whole planet, quiet.

CRICKET:
God bless America.

Gunny closes the circuit on the third tube.

The shell rides its spark up past the flags, up past the white
sphere's last embers, and breaks BLUE-WHITE, dead center over the
ring, a sphere that swells until it takes the entire frame —

WHITE OUT.

Hold in the white. Silence.

CUT TO:


EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

Days later. The party looks lived-in now: cable runs, a supply
line of cases walked over from the Harmony lander, the flags
holding their ring.

At the lander, load-up. Stitch and Dutch carry the last cases up
the ramp. Gunny walks crate F's remaining stores the other way,
toward the base station, stacking them neat without being asked.

Brandt watches Cricket, who has not started for the ramp.

BRANDT:
We have four couches rigged.

CRICKET:
Three's enough.

Brandt looks at him. At the ring of flags. Back at him. Then he
nods once, and goes to supervise the loading.

Dutch comes down the ramp with his binder. He opens the rings,
pulls a section — pages of margins, tables, his own handwriting —
and hands them over.

DUTCH:
Consumable margins, four pages. The scrubber schedule is
non-negotiable. It's initialed.

CRICKET:
It would be.

Gunny sets the last stores case down, squares it to the stack, and
faces Cricket. He doesn't say anything. He comes to attention and
holds out his hand, and they shake, one pump, done.

Stitch is last, at the foot of the ramp.

STITCH:
Same time Tuesday.

CRICKET:
I'll have the net up.

Stitch climbs the ramp without looking back.

INT. HARMONY ONE, CABIN - LATER

Cramped. Three old men webbed into rigged restraints among three
astronauts in couches, knees and elbows everywhere. Foil-wrapped
burgers pass hand to hand, cold.

Lindqvist takes two, holds one out to Shen wedged beside him.

Shen looks at it. Takes it. Unwraps it, and eats.

Nobody says anything about it. Dutch, chewing, produces his pencil
and starts a fuel-margin calculation on the foil.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

Cricket stands clear of the blast radius, alone by the ring.

The ascent engine lights, silent. The lander rises on its spark,
up and over, dust settling in slow sheets. He holds a salute
until it's one bright point among the stars.

Then he turns, and walks back to the flags, bootprints joining the
hundreds already there.

CUT TO:


INT. ROY'S DINER - DAY

Months on. The TV, sound low: C-SPAN. The vote board fills green.

CHYRON: RESTORATION OF FLIGHT STATUS ACT PASSES 98-2. BACKUP CREWS
OF THE APOLLO PROGRAM ENTERED INTO THE ROLLS.

BUCK:
Who were the two?

EARLENE:
Does it matter?

BUCK:
I'd like to know their addresses is all.

The Cook sets a plate in front of a stranger. The carbon meter is
gone off the gas line. Four screw holes where it sat.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - DAY

Peg at the table with the mail. She opens a government envelope —
linen again, eagle again.

INSERT — A PAY STUB: DAWES, E. — RANGER (FIRST), TRANQUILITY BASE
NATIONAL HISTORIC PARK. And a number, a real one, with digits.

Peg reads it twice. Puts it under a magnet on the fridge, square,
where the family can see it.

The hutch drawer with the old check in it stays shut.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT (TUESDAY)

The simulator hums on standby. DANNY sits at the ham rig with a
mug, headset on, logbook open — a fresh spiral notebook, his own
handwriting on the spine.

DANNY:
(into the mic)
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Here.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
On time for once, son.

A pause. Static, long-traveled, three seconds of light-lag round
trip.

CRICKET (FILTERED):
(far, thin, clear)
Tranquility. Reading you loud and clear.

Danny grins at the rig and writes the time in the log.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE NATIONAL HISTORIC PARK - LUNAR NIGHT

A small hab module sits off the original site, resupply pods
beside it. A carved sign faces the bootprint trail:

TRANQUILITY BASE NATIONAL HISTORIC PARK — EST. JULY 4 — RANGER
STATION NO. 1.

The six flags stand their ring, colors lit by Earthlight. Over the
hab, on its workshop pole, the fifty-one-star flag.

CRICKET — suit patched at the knee, an arrowhead park patch on his
chest — walks the ring's perimeter, checking each staff with one
glove, a firm pull at each.

He finishes at the first flag, the one from 1969, and looks up.

The Earth hangs full above the flags, night side facing — dark
continents rimmed in city light.

Cricket raises one glove, all the way, and waves.

A beat.

On the dark face of the Earth: a city flickers. Then another. Then
whole coastlines, pulsing — two, pause, two — the wave rolling
westward across the night side, city by city, sea to sea.

Cricket holds his glove up, and the Earth keeps answering, and the
flags hold their colors in the black.

FADE OUT.

> **THE END** <


